column3: I haven't had Dunkin Donuts in years. Being that I had to fuel up my work truck I decided against my better judgment to order a toasted everything bagel with vegetable cream cheese which I had to repeat 3 times. Used my card to pay for my order, received my bag and walked out to my work truck. Opened my bagel to see plain cream cheese. Walk back into Dunkin Donuts and repeated myself for the 4th time. They throw out that bagel and go to back to prepare a new bagel. A few seconds later she comes back with "We have no vegetable cream cheese. All we have is plain and strawberry." My response was "You didn't know that since you started your shift?" Never again will I buy anything from any Dunkin Donuts...

column3: First time here. I was early for a private event and, since it's more important to mingle at those things than eat, and I had not eaten, I ordered the lasagna ($23). It was very good and the portion was generous. My only reservation is that all entres should be served piping hot and it was only warm.  The wait staff, though, was exceptionally accommodating. Even before I had even planned to order, they allowed me a seat in the bar area near an outlet to charge my depleted phone.  This place is about a mile from the Fulton Landing/Dumbo ferry and the walk through Columbia /Brooklyn Heights is one of the most scenic in the city. So as a Manhattan resident, I'll be bringing my family here one weekend night soon.

column3: This is hands-down the best pizzeria in the area. It‚Äôs better than Julianas, Grimaldi‚Äôs and Ignazios. Dellaroccos comes close but this place is superior overall (the pizzas come in larger size options and are all amazing, larger restaurant with more seating options and better bar service/better drink options). I recommend the ‚Äúfrozen negroni‚Äù cocktail, but if you dont like the bitterness of a negroni then you will not like it. I recommend sitting in the back around the corner because they have good air conditioning back there. I liked the pizza that has nduja on it, I think they also have a truffle oil pizza that my wife and I also enjoyed. column3: We are loyal customers of Table 87 for many years and have recommended the establishment, including the restaurant on Third Avenue and the most newest spot, located in Industry City, During my recent visit, I ordered takeout.  The staff that prepared the food were two gentlemen.  They were rude and did not treat me in a professional and engaging manner. When my pies were presented, I asked for garlic, the same request that I always ask for, but this time, the server replied, in an annoying manner, " over there!" I apologized and asked again for garlic, but the roasted garlic that Table 87 is famous for. The server grunted and yelled out for an order to be bought to the front of the store. During this time, I noticed that three other patrons arrived, for take out, and were greeted nicely, and time was given to assist them with their order.  Now, I understand that the two male employees are capable of carrying out the duties of providing customer service because they clearly treated me in a rather unpleasant and uncalled manner. I did not ask for handouts.  Furthermore, my appearance was clean and sharp.  My diction was clear and succinct.  My manner was tempered and respectful. There was no just cause to be mistreated  and to be made to feel less valued than my counterparts who patronized Table 87 at Atlantic Avenue.  Thank you.

ORIGINAL REVIEW: I've been there 2 times for the last two weeks. Both times I was served by an Asian guy. He alone deserves all my 5 stars. Most of the other subway restaurants employees just throw stuff into my sandwich like there's a fire.

column3: I think this place is overrated, at least for our experience. We were not so happy with the food, scrubled eggs and fried chicken (schnitzel) were very salty and the chicked didn‚Äôt look good at all. The lemon tahini squash were so raw and undercooked, they were so nice to send a new order and take them off our check. column3: Gertie left us with mixed feelings. While the hipster ambiance adds flair, a 30+ minute Sunday wait for a party of four dampened the experience, especially when neighboring restaurants boasted available seating. The staff's cool and friendly demeanor softened the blow of mediocre food, but the bialy breakfast and bacon egg & cheese sandwich failed to justify their steep prices. At $16 for a sandwich, we expected a taste that transcends, yet it fell short. In the realm of brunch options, Gertie seems more about hype than substance. For those seeking value and prompt service, other neighborhood eateries may offer a more satisfying experience.

column3: This is restaurant is yummy! If you love potatoes you‚Äôve come to the right place, enough potatoes to keep you full for one week of potato-kind-of cravings. I love this spot! It‚Äôs bright and sunny, beautifully decorated, native New Yorker owned and full of delicious food.  The brown butter chocolate chip cookie is the perfect size and has delicious chips and a wonderfully butt‚Äôry and crumbly crumb.  The chocolate marzipan babka was EXCELLENT!!! A perfect combo of almond croissant and pain au chocolat but WITHOUT any of the dry outer crust that I usually end up peeling off and throwing away because it‚Äôs not as delish as the moist interior. With this babka, you can just stick the whole thing in your gullet and every bite is excellent. Butt‚Äôry, moist, almondy chocolate doughy delight! Definitely get this!  The everything bagel was sumptuous and sensual and I put some buttah on it and it really made my life complete. Highly recommend!  GERTIE makes its baked goods in-house and they take a lot of pride in making them excellent. Also, I‚Äôm glad they have matcha so I can cancel out all the sugar with a little bit of healthy bittnerness, which is different than the unhealthy bitterness many of us tend to carry within us for various reasons! Check out GERTIE and let them know I sent ya!

column3: Having grown up on NY bagels and deli sandwiches, Gertie is like a haven to me when I'm in the mood to sit somewhere and enjoy these staples done right. The textures and flavors of their house made bagels, pastries, and breads are spot on, and their sandwiches always hit the spot.  While I have tried nearly every sandwich on the menu, I always find myself coming back to the Reuben. I consider this particular sandwich to be my personal cheat code for feeling right. Gertie's version nails the proportions with thick cuts of corned beef and just the right amount of dressing, kraut, and cheese. I always get it with a side of fingerling potatoes + house aioli and wash it down with their draft cold brew, which is very smooth and my favorite in the neighborhood.  I've also gotta say that the staff at Gertie are fun and super attentive, which is a big part of the reason why I keep coming back (almost) every week. As far as the space itself goes, the place is bathed in natural light, which makes it feel like a breath of fresh air after being in my tiny apartment for hours on end. Just go, enjoy, and tip your server!

column3: The Gerties comes closest to what we in Berlin call a mother-and-child cafe with an eco twist. First of all, it's incredibly loud. You will look in vain for breakfast a la a nice large plate with cheese, sausage, fruit, jam, cream cheese and other gadgets. We switch to Plates & Bowls, more precisely to the Gerties House Special. Ultimately, the plate was also a bagel, only opened up and everything that normally goes in the bagel was separated into small bowls. Was a little funny too. However, it cost $18, a lot more than a bagel. The cafe itself is bright, there is a large window front, and the preparation takes place directly behind a counter. The dishes are colorful and thrown together.

column3: We start with the most important item - food. Food is not good, it is AMAZING!!! Truly is, I an no stranger to middle eastern food and I did not recognize all the dips and spices use. The shrimps were succulent and huge. the lamb chops perfectly seared and seasoned. Fries are cooked to perfection, home made bread is unique. truly great. The servers were friendly and accommodating , BUT, and that is a big BUT - They need to be on top of their game! 1. Short changing us with the wine pour. 2. Not knowing what we ordered. 3. Not placing our ordered, so starving us had to wait 20 extra minutes. They made up for it with an on the house dessert. Yes, we will be back but PLEASE, This is not a cheap thrill and not for the budget conscious. When we splurge, We want a return!!

column3: I recently had the pleasure of dining at this fantastic restaurant, and I cannot praise it enough! From the moment I stepped inside, I was captivated by the ethantic ambiance and warm, welcoming atmosphere. It truly felt like a hidden gem tucked away from the bustling city.  Let's talk about the food‚Äîit was absolutely divine! Every dish I tried was prepared with the utmost care and attention to detail. The flavors burst in my mouth, and it was evident that only the freshest ingredients were used. I appreciate their commitment to maintaining a high standard of quality.  Moreover, the staff here deserves special mention. The servers were attentive, friendly, and knowledgeable about the menu. They were more than happy to make recommendations and accommodate any dietary preferences or restrictions. Their genuine passion for the cuisine and dedication to ensuring an exceptional dining experience truly stood out.  I have visited this restaurant multiple times, and I can confidently say that I have never been disappointed. The consistency in the quality of both the food and service is commendable. It's rare to find a place that consistently delivers such an outstanding experience.  Whether you're looking for a romantic dinner, a casual meal with friends, or a special celebration, this restaurant is an excellent choice. I highly recommend trying their Mana'eesh it's an absolute delight!  In conclusion, I wholeheartedly endorse this restaurant. Its ethantic charm, fresh and delectable cuisine, and attentive staff make it a standout dining destination. I can't wait to return and savor more of their culinary delights.

column3: My friend and I decided to try Lebanese for the first time at this establishment in the East Village, already being familiar with other cuisines of the Middle East. All the inside tables were full, so we decided to eat outside despite the heat - and we sure were glad we did! We got Almaza beers from Lebanon, which were served with a salt-rimmed glass. I had never experienced this with a beer before, but let me tell you, on a hot summer day, a light crisp beer like that with a salted glass is just heavenly. Then for food we got Spicy Falafel, Halloum, Babaganoush, and these little Lebanese marinated sausages with pine nuts whose name i unfortunately forget, but they were absolutely delicious. All the food was top notch. Halloum is like a stiffer mozzarella with a flavor of char from being grilled. The service was very fast and friendly. I would definitely return to this location and I will definitely be eating Lebanese food again given the opportunity. It was outstanding.

column3: If I could put zero star, I would. My mom was visiting and I wanted to have her a good Lebanese‚Äôs shawarma and good NYC experience. BOY I was so wrong! We visited here last Saturday, on July 29th. It was a very HOT day outside. I grew up in a hot climate so my mother and I have high tolerance to heat, but when we entered the restaurant, the restaurant was INFERNO, there was no central cooling system, just a couple of fans, which were clearly not good enough for the whole restaurant. The waiters were serving lukewarm water. My mother who never drinks iced water, asked THREE times for ice, until the waiter brought ice in a glass. We ordered table lamb Shawarma, the next table also ordered table shawarma. Since shawarma tables had to be plugged in and there were not enough outlets, the waiters turned off our only fan, and plugged in our next table shawarma. So the situation turned to intolerable! No matter how many times we asked, the waiters didn‚Äôt do anything since the next door guys wanted the shawarma plugged in. My mother and I couldn‚Äôt eat and we were sweating profusely. It was like we were eating in a dry Sauna. We left. It was a HORRIBLE HORRIBLE experience and guess what I was charged 150 dollars for a very dry lamb shawarma!

column3: I came here with two friends after wanting to come for a while. We had a later reservation but the restaurant was still very crowded with no signs of it closing down for the night. There was no AC, just several fans, which made it a bit uncomfortable on an 86 degree day, but we did cool down a bit. The food was all very good, but our server was one of the worst I have ever had in New York. We had to practically beg for water refills, and when we ordered a bottle of wine, he eventually came back and said they didn‚Äôt have it. We then chose 3 alternates, none of which they had in stock. The only suggestion he gave us was one $20 over what we had requested. We ended up just picking a completely different wine just because we were tired of going back and forth. The rest of the meal, our waiter just obviously did not want to be there. I was honestly shocked with his level of attitude as we were definitely a relaxed party and not aggressively asking for much. By the time we got the bill it was clear he wanted us to leave. I am typically always a 20% tipper no matter what, but his service was so poor it severely affected our experience. I‚Äôm honestly unsure if I‚Äôd come back, as I‚Äôve had much better service at Laser Wolf and Cafe Mogador.

I really wanted to give this place 5 stars but the heart of Lebanese cuisine is the meat, and the meat here is disastrously dry, both the chicken and the beef.  Other than that, the sauces and spreads (toum, lebneh, hummus) are amazing and pita is incredibly soft and clearly fresh. Maybe if you‚Äôre vegetarian, this might be a great spot for you, but if you want real middle eastern meat, this place is truly under-whelming. This place has been my family's absolute favorite pizza place for... maybe the last 8 or 9 years. We were living in Manhattan, and I'd bring my daughter here when we were visiting Bayside or Whitestone to go hunting for an apartment. When we found a place in Bayside, I actually (I swear to you) considered Freddy's one of the reasons for which I was happy to have moved into this area. The funny thing is, we almost never get the pizza. It's always their creamy Penne a la Vodka (served with warm Italian bread) and a large Chicken Caesar Salad... my daughter wouldn't eat salad in any other style, or from any other place. It's incredible. The guys there have been there for years, down to earth and decent ppl. Back in the pre-COVID days, you could sit in their dining area that had about a dozen 2 and 4 seat tables, and it was cozy and just a nice, bright atmosphere. If you're looking for a new neighborhood fave for pizza and home style Italian, try it.

For a simple dish that I did not agree with the cost, it was $19 (plus $7 juice) it was $26 with $1.69 tax (which is not correct, it is 8.875%) and they add a $5.20 tip without asking if that is my tip option. It makes a total of $32.89. Now you have to be aware of what charges they make because for a one-dish service they always want to get money from you like a restaurant in Manhattan. They won the day but lost a regular customer.

Dylan Candy Bar was undoubtedly the worst experience of my trip to the United States. I decided to buy some chocolate bars to treat my friends. I spotted a promotional offer: 4 for $14, so I picked up 8. When I got to the cashier and made two stacks of 4, the server seemed puzzled and was far from pleasant. She quickly provided a price, but I tried to explain that it was for a gift and asked if she could wrap them. She looked at me with annoyance, sighed, and pointed to the card payment. She didn't offer a receipt or bid me goodbye.  A few minutes later, a friend joined me, irritated because he noticed that the discount hadn't been applied. He politely pointed it out to her, but she responded by rolling her eyes and being uncooperative. Without a receipt, I checked my mobile payment app and realized the discount hadn't been applied. I asked for an explanation, but instead of helping, the staff became increasingly unpleasant. Eventually, after a 5-minute battle, my app indicated the refund, and the cashier mumbled a sarcastic "clever." I left, hearing her angrily throw a cardboard box.  I've seen such practices before, where speaking quickly, not providing a receipt, and insisting on incorrect payments are common tactics to deceive foreigners. I strongly advise any foreigner against stopping at this establishment.

column3: Sadly this IHOP location has gone extremely downhill in quality. There was only one person working front of house, she was the host, waitress, and food runner. Couple that with 5 tables to take care of meant that we sat for 30 minutes before we had our order taken. The biggest fault, and the main reason I'll never come back, was the sodas. We were served completely flat Pepsi. Basically sweet brown water. We weren't even given the decency to be told they only had flat soda or even told they have no soda. We were served that at $4 a glass with a straight face. Never again. The food itself came out fast, and was mediocre but the prices were too expensive. Because of all these reasons I would highly recommend that you do not come here under any circumstance.

We called late last night for friends who arrived from out of town bit craved some Chinese. My regular place was closed at 10. Was shocked to learn they closed at 9.30.  Remember when that would have been unheard of in Manhattan? This place too, was closing bit they were so kind, and took our order delivering a delicious hot meal. They ordered Shrimp with Lobster Sauce. The shrimps were large and fresh, a tofu dish which was light and so delicious, the egg rolls and spring rolls were just as they should be, vegetable dumplings were ample (not thin) and tasty. Someone wanted cod sesame noodles and he dish as quite yummy. All else we ordered was just very nice and delicious. They included plenty of accouchements. The plastics were not flimsy but nice too. I recommend using this very pleasantly run establishment. And , I also thank them  being so very kind and going the extra mile.    Ë¨ùË¨ù

Sauce on the Lo Mein could probably have used a bit more flavor‚Ä¶ not sure if it needed more salt or what but something was missing.  The vegetable spring rolls were phenomenal however. I came home from the airport at 11:30 pm after a 15 hour flight from Shanghai to New York. In the cab on the way home, I desperately began to hunt on seamless trying to find anything to fill my belly. I saw "Szechuan chili house"'and thought to myself, this must be a mistake. How can a Chinese place, on the east side, deliver to me, on the west side at 12 am? My skeptical thoughts were put to an end once I called and confirmed that I could indeed put Chinese food in my mouth within the next half hour.  Even though I love authentic szechuanese food, I stuck with the good old American General tsao and pork fried rice. 25 minutes later, a chilly and shivering chinamen handed over the goods and I rushed back upstairs.  I ripped the bag open and was greeted with crispy, sweet, and delicious fresh white meat General tsao. It wasn't the best I've had, but I was completely satisfied considering the fact I put in an order around midnight. If you are up in the late hours in the night and want something other than dominoes or insomnia cookies, give Wa Jeal Szechuan chili house a try.

column3: Nestled in the heart of Park Slope, a picturesque neighborhood adorned with historic brownstones and tree-lined avenues, lies "Daisy's Diner" - a culinary gem that has stood the test of time. With 60 years in Park Slope and 30 under the same dedicated owner, this diner is a testament to timeless charm and culinary excellence.  Park Slope is a vibrant tapestry of families, young professionals, and open-minded individuals. The eclectic blend of indie boutiques, trendy eateries, and cozy bakeries along 5th and 7th Avenues makes it a haven for both locals and visitors. And as the leaves turn golden in the fall, the family-friendly ambiance of the area becomes even more enchanting.  Stepping into Daisy's Diner is like taking a delightful trip down memory lane. The classic diner ambiance, complete with the familiar counter seating, evokes a sense of nostalgia. While the decor remains largely unchanged (save for some modern light fixtures), the food is as mouthwatering as ever.  I vividly recall stepping into this quaint nook one Saturday morning, fresh from a fishing expedition with my buddies. As we regaled each other with tales of our maritime adventures, each story more grandiose than the last, the owner would sit by the counter, chuckling behind his morning paper, clearly entertained by our exaggerated recounts. Every so often, as a nod to our spirited storytelling, he'd treat the "brave sea conquerors" to a complimentary stack of what he fondly termed "flapjacks." I suspect it was his subtle way of silencing our boisterous tales, but we loved every bite of it!  On my recent visit, I indulged in a scrumptious plate of scrambled eggs with cheddar, crispy bacon, and perfectly seasoned potatoes peppered with onions. Each bite was a delightfully diner fare, reminding me of why I fell in love with this place a 45 years ago. The potatoes were notably fresh, non-greasy, and cooked to perfection.  Just as I remembered way back when.  I guess it's because they have the same cook from back then.  Though Daisy's may seem like a modest "hole in the wall" to some, it's a treasure trove of deliciousness. The swift service, coupled with the warm, freshly prepared dishes, makes every visit worthwhile.  In conclusion, if you're in Park Slope and seeking a classic diner experience that's both authentic and delectable, Daisy's Diner is the place to be. Here's to many more years of delightful dishes and cherished memories! üç≥ü•ìüçÅ

column3: I chose Daisy‚Äôs Diner because I needed a relaxing place outside of my home to do some late night work. Unfortunately, I left so angry because of the racism I experienced that I can barely stand to type this review.  Upon entering, the man (perhaps the owner and I need not say he also was white) beckoned me with his finger to get service. When I asked him to clarify which tables were free, he asked me whether I could speak English.  I grew up in NYC and honestly have not heard words like that since the 1990s. column3: I'm told this place has been around for a while... and is on at least it's 2nd owner ...it has total charm.  I liked it... the place just keeps going back further and further with row after row of cool 'secluded type' booth seating ...to a window in the back looking out at a parking lot and 'mod type' tallish building.  There is an exit door to the parking lot but I don't know if it is used a lot.  We sat in the back.  Lots of room.  The whole place is a 'frayed at the edges' / 'lived in' but totally lovable.  It is not dirty but 'worn.'  It is an 'aged nicely' look like someone would buy at IKEA (a 'distressed' piece of furniture, that is).  I should have brought my camera-phone to take pictures... there are 'picture worthy' things.  It was a second night out for me and the extended family ...Mom, her (our) friend and part of the family that were somewhere else for Thanksgiving were there (six of us).  It was roomy and they were very accommodating at Daisy's ...the waitress was on her game and attentive.  Refills, extras items... good friendly attitude.  I ordered 'Cajun Glazed' Chicken... it was tasty, came out on three plates & a fourth to hold a gravy cup (that I shared with my friend right across from who had a brisket sliced thing on mashed potatoes.  "It was a good amount of food" (and could have easily fed me and someone else or be 'take home' as well) I think that is the idea here... as I looked at everyone having 'LG Size potions.'  Like I said... it's been here a while and the patrons plus staff are laid back (but not lazy) ...like a comfortable living room (it's the local living room for sure) ...or like the 'clubhouse' you and your friends had with a bunch of different types of furniture (and a patched hole in a bench seat).  I want to stress again that the food was good... large amounts, decent prices ...and the surroundings, charming, cozy... to include good service and round the clock hours.  No one in my group even mentioned anything that put them off and we all just enjoyed the eating and talking (like everyone else there in their own private worlds).

column3: The most delicious meal I've experienced so far this year. Underrated, unfussy, incredibly clear flavor profiles, and the Mezcal pairings were impeccably done. There are no glowing signs to attract your attention, in a nondescript part of Park Slope, a simple intimate ground floor setting. The food was incredible, from the first bite to the last. The short rib mole was indeed the most memorable, but the rest was a close second. Never had a Mezcal pairing with food before, but this clean freshness of some seriously authentic Mexican flavors, coupled with the smoky and sweet at times, I will not soon forget. I hope to return often. One Michelin star, very affordable, with the largest Mezcal collection I've ever seen. Whatever your notion of Mexican cuisine, this will not disappoint.

column3: Amazing and lovely presentation of their items. Their mezcal selection is lovely and unique. Their veal garnachas are a must and blew me away. Delish. Their moles were delicious, I got the red mole and my boyfriend got the black mole. The meat in our mole was falling apart and the dish was well composed, although I felt like the red mole was a little too salty. The rice was white, and although was seasoned, I felt like the right pairing should have been red rice. Please do not hesitate to get the peach rice pudding if it‚Äôs in the menu because even though we were stuffed, we couldn‚Äôt stop eating it.

column3: Excellent, fairly-priced meal. The food is downright finger-lickin‚Äô good. If you‚Äôre not already familiar with Oaxacan cuisine and mezcal, this meal will be eye-opening and educational. Portion sizes are big enough to make you leave absolutely stuffed, yet the judicious use of vegetables prevents the meal from becoming too heavy.  The mole doesn‚Äôt come with tortillas. You should order a stack. Claro is proud of their masa, made in-house with criollo corn imported from Oaxaca. What a difference that makes! The tortilla are soft, as if they dutifully followed a skincare routine, and almost fluffy‚Äîjust as satisfying as eating rice.  Claro is more than a restaurant. It‚Äôs also a mezcal bar. In hindsight, I should‚Äôve gotten the mezcal pairing instead of a cocktail. I thought all mezcals will be smoke-bombs, but that‚Äôs far from the truth! It‚Äôs a liquor with a rich tradition and a wide range of flavors, like wine or sake. If you‚Äôre not familiar with mezcal, please don‚Äôt order cocktails; give mezcal a chance.  Service is excellent. The staff are warm and knowledgeable. They‚Äôll guide you through the menu and explain the traditions behind the drinks.  Claro has a Michelin star, yet they don‚Äôt mention it anywhere on the website or premises. They let the food speak for themselves. I personally think they‚Äôre on the higher end of the one stars, especially for the value delivered at that price.

column3: I unfortunately did not have a good experience at brunch Sunday. The service was subpar not due to their performance but due to the poor management not knowing when their restaurant is actually busy.  The drinks took about an hour to come out after we sat down. The drinks themselves were pretty good in comparison. It was just coffee and bellini, nothing complicated.  I ordered an omelette that took even longer to come out. It was overcooked and hard. It had hair on it (pictured). The waiter took the dish back and gave me $1.50 off. Normally when you have hair show up in your food you would get a new dish or the item comped. Taking off $1.50 just made the experience worse on top of the service.  For that experience, I had to pay 20% gratuity (included in the bill) and then are asked to tip even more on the receipt. The management seriously needs to reconsider how they staff this place and treat situations where there is hair in the food.

column3: My family and I love Italian food, and therefore have high standards when choosing an Italian place to eat at.  Yesterday, my daughter made our decision much more difficult by being in a mood, so we picked what we closest...and boy did we make a great decision.  As we were seated street-side outside, we were placed opposite a husband-wife jazz duo on the corner who played beautiful music.  As our appetizers and cocktails came out, they floored us and were the best we've had in the city since arriving nearly a week ago.  As for our main dishes, each of our four dishes we chose were completely different but each one was absolutely stunning.  The sauces each had unique tastes and balance and there was a sufficient amount of meat and noodle in each.  We left very satisfied.  I'll leave with this place has absolutely ruined Italian food for us...because I don't think any Italian food can compete with this ever again.  I cannot wait to come back to this city and come back to Mama Mia's on 44th.

column3: I hadn‚Äôt been to this restaurant since pre-Covid, but I had always loved to come here for the desserts and sangria (the sangria is a must).  Recently, I came here on a date and the experience left not just me, but my date perplexed lol. The waitress at our table came around a little more than necessary to check on us. I‚Äôm talking mid conversation, we were being interrupted by the waitress. It became so frequent that it‚Äôs now a personal insider between us ‚Äúneed anything?‚Äù. While I appreciate the service, it was incredibly excessive and I‚Äôm not sure what the deal with that was. Awkward to say the very least.  Moving on to the food, my pasta was hardly warm when it got to the table. An odd temperature, for sure. Bread had been set on the table for us, but it was swiftly taken away before we could even touch it and was replaced by the bill before we requested it (by the same waitress who kept intruding at our table). We still joke about being ‚Äúkicked out‚Äù because that‚Äôs what it felt like. The restaurant wasn‚Äôt even full (it was a Sunday evening) and there were plenty of other diners taking it easy and relaxing.  The nerve of it all was when the waitress asked us if we wanted dessert. Maybe we would‚Äôve been more inclined to do so if we hadn‚Äôt been rushed through our meal. column3: The food was okay. I did not enjoy the vibe and interior. I won't come back to this place.

My mother and I were in the area and wanted some Italian cuisine so we stopped by to check it out. When we arrived, we wanted to check out the menu they had out front to make sure they had the food we were interested in potentially getting. The hostess ran outside to greet us and then stared at us until we decided that we would try it out. It was uncomfortable how desperate they seemed to want to get customers in the door. Our waiter came by our table and wasn't very friendly at first, but then made a quick joke with us and took our drink order. We got the drinks pretty quickly and our food order was taken. We ordered an appetizer together and then each got an entree. The entrees came out first and when we asked about the appetizer, he said that they were making it fresh and it would be nice and hot (however, we specifically asked to start with the appetizer). We didn't end up getting the appetizer until we were about halfway done with our meal. Our waiter NEVER came by to check on us or ask how our meal was. Someone else came by and asked to clear our plates and we asked for a a couple of boxes for our leftovers. He came back with boxes and a bag, and we bagged everything up and then waited about 10 minutes for our check. Once our waiter came and took our card, he left with it and then was just talking to people at the bar. He handed over a bunch of checks to a waitress and she finished the transaction with us. This was not a good experience overall. The food was average, nothing to rave about. The ambience was nice and cozy which I enjoyed, but that was about it.
Service was horrible. They moved charges. They did not deliver some things. They took large amounts of time. We did have a larger group but still.

column3: What a great discovery.  Was in NYC and need a spot for pre-theater dinner with my Niece.  Mama Mia was a short walk from the parking garage and and even closer to the theater.  I ordered the Aperol Spritz. It was perfectly made. Our meal consisted of a side of Meatballs. Perfect Grandma Style Meatballs. Crispy outside, moist and full of flavor inside. Smothered in the house Marinara. Samantha had Basil Pesto with Chicken and Sundried Tomatos. She cleaned the plate and it was a huge portion. She really  loved it. I had one of the best Eggplant Parmasean dinners ever. Thin layers of creamy....almost meaty Eggplant stacked high. Smothered with delicious Grandma style sauce and perfectly finished with cheese.  Not fancy. Attentive staff and service. Here it's all about the food. Generous portions, served hot and full of slow cooked flavor. All that with fair prices for the quality of the food this is a solid neighborhood spot.  Mama Mia has been in business for 51 years. They're clearly getting the food right.

column3: I hosted a private event at Oliver's, and it was a seamless experience from start to finish, all of which is attributed to the people I've worked with throughout various stages of the event (thank you so much Kim, Phil, and Hannah!)  I booked the Landmark Lounge, which is their private rooms downstairs, for a surprise 30th birthday party for my husband. It was the perfect size for the 20 of us (plenty of sitting and standing space), and is beautifully decorated throughout. As this was for a birthday party, we got minimal decor in black and gold, which matched perfectly with the color scheme of the space.  There is no rental fee for the space, but there is a minimum that must be met via food and/or drinks - note that it's not just the host's bill, but everyone else's bill that contributes to meeting the minimum. Because I had ordered an assortment of food platters for the party, I had already surpassed the minimum myself, but it's great to know for those looking for an affordable/easy minimum option.  As for the event itself, the quality of service we've received was top notch - from my constant back and forth emails with Kim about the event, to doing a mini tour of the venue with Phil and him taking care of all my concerns (before and during the event), to Hannah effortlessly serving our group of 20 and making sure we all had a drink in our hands, I was impressed and blown away. They really went above and beyond to make sure I was happy with everything and I truly appreciate the level of attentiveness they carried through the entirety of the event.  The food was all delicious - you can order platters ahead of time, and the serving sizes are quite generous. I over-ordered for my group, which is fine (better that than not ordering enough), as my guests happily took home leftovers. Drinks were very reasonably priced and delicious as well!  I really can't thank the staff enough for all their hard work - needless to say, I HIGHLY recommend Oliver's if you're looking to host a private event as I promise you will be taken care of!

I almost never write reviews , but i believe it's time to start writing. The hospitality in big cities is terrible and it's getting worse , it's ridiculous .  The places with already built names and good locations are doing fine and making money with terrible customer service , while most of the business are struggling , so i just want to help the places that they are not well known with good customer service, they deserve more attention. Just to direct people where to spend their money for an already overpriced city with terrible hospitality !  This place had a big video projector showing the World Cup games , it was Thursday so I decided to watch the game .  Guessing that they want to attract customers interested in World Cup i stop by and i was very clear with the host that i would like to watch the game and have few drinks , the video projector was in the middle of the restaurant so you cant watch it from the bar , she gave me a small standing table near the video projector  . The restaurant was not full .  Meanwhile the restaurant get busier , i already had two margaritas it was after second half when she approach me telling me that they have reservation for that table , clearly they wanted to fit more people , she suggest me to move on the bar which was full and it was very hard to watch the game from that position . I paid my check i didn't leave a tip and i left the place , one block away i found much better service .  If you show the game especially with projector then you are inviting people to watch the game , i guess is weekday and you believe you will need some extra profit from the game (from drinks) , in contrary if you are confident and you have enough customers then you don't play the game , or maybe just the bar .  You just don't do those things !
Thank you for great food and happiest customer service!! Appreciate you!

I'd like to preface that this might have been a bad day for them, but my experience here was pretty terrible and we very likely wont be coming back.  My partner ordered a double smashburger that ended up being dry and gray with no caramelization at all and I ordered the tomahawk pork chop that was as dry as leather and pretty hard to eat.  After 40 minutes of sitting at the table being served lukewarm water, the food finally came. The flavors were good, and could have been great and the presentation WAS great, but if it's not cooked properly that doesnt make up for it.  I mentioned to the waitress, who was pretty inattentive about the problem, and even extra sauce could not make the pork edible. The restaurant was not busy either, with maybe 2 other parties and a couple people drinking.  After we finished and asked for the check, they tried to charge us $29 instead of $19 for the again, gray burger which we luckily caught just for them to say they typed 2 instead of 1 on their current up-to-date P.O.S. somehow.  This was a $45 meal. No excuse.

Horrible.  First of all no one speaks English in here. Had to wait about 5 mins for someone to come out of the back that "speaks English" but she really doesn't speak English. Pretty much tells me they don't care about your business if your not fluent in Spanish.  I ordered a 3 piece fried chicken. The chicken is seasoned really well. The problem is it's nearly impossible to get a fresh piece of chicken. Seems like the chicken is fried once or twice a day and just sits under a heating lamp all day. The breading is stale, this should be expected for chicken that was cooked hours ago.  Another thing that pissed me off was that this is one of those places that doesn't add tax to their prices UNLESS you pay with your card. And the tax isn't really tax, it's to cover their transaction fees. I hate when business do this. It's illegal (I work in credit card processing, I know what I'm talking about). Long story short this is a horribly ran business, I'll never go back inside of this place. Stale food, no one speaks English and they charge your card for an amount that is higher than what they tell you to pay.

The food is good but I think they're showing false advertisement with having the sticker posted saying they accept cards and PayPal. My wife said she's used her card before and so have a few of my friends. When I go though and I pull out my card I am told to use the ATM. It's already happened twice and that's enough for me to take my business elsewhere. I've been in customer service for over 15 years and I was trained to give the same experience to every customer every time, not act like you take cards only during day and make people use the ATM at night. It's a shame because I was going to give them way more business because they said they were accepting cards now. One star lost for false advertisement and two stars lost for each time I was told to use the ATM.

column3: Worst curry I have ever had and that includes some I made in grad school from a jar using a microwave. - 40% giant pieces of onions - random other stuff that was not supposed to in there, like roasted potatoes and fried tofu - barely any of the ingredients that the menu said you are getting.  Three pieces of eggplant and a few leaves of tasteless basil. -The actual curry sauce?  Consistency of a soup.  Basically, take a quarter of a jar of leftover curry sauce, rinse it out with equal amount of water.  There you have it.  I would have sent my food back except this was the evening when I was saying goodbye to my son who is just starting college.  And at least his sesame chicken looked decent.  Service:  it started out good with a smiling waitress bringing us iced water.  Then I asked for water without ice instead (really cold things don‚Äôt agree with me), and that was the end of the smiles.  The place is supposed to be open until 10:00. But already at 9:20 people kept coming by to see if we were ready to get out.  I was holding chopsticks in my hand when one of them asked if he should take my plate.  Too bad because the place looked so nice.  The look (interesting interior, nice custom printed napkins, pretty tableware) is why I am not giving one star but two.

column3: Went to Nikko restaurant with my family twice. The service was excellent. The food sushi, General Tso's Chicken, Schezuan Beef, soup, deserts, drinks were excellent as well. I love the ambiance, the lighting was perfect. Only thing is that people at the bar and hibachi area can get loud and annoying but have some warm sake and you will fit right in. I really like this place since Hunan Balcony and our other favorite restaurant China Fun closed, this is definitely my family's new favorite restaurant.  This is an Update: July 9th 2023***  My family and I have ordered Nikko for delivery through UberEats several times but today my family member ordered two different dinners soups and salads including an appetizer crab Shumai. Food seemed a bit unorganized and shuffled in the bag but bag was stapled as usual, everything was spilled and leaking that was unusual generally when when we received an order every thing is organized and no soups leaking.  Upon eating two  bites of the shrimp and broccoli and General Tso's and crab Shumai. I immediately threw up, this food was completely rotten and had a chemically taste. I cannot believe we ate some of this rotten food, everything had to be thrown out immediately after consuming a bit of the food we all became ill from the chemically taste and realized the putrid smells fumigating from the bag it was delivered in this is definitely a food safety issue  and I hope the food inspectors will investigate thier kitchen and cooks  Unfortunately we will not be ordering again. I hope this restaurant will realize just how fast they can lose great customers by not checking the quality of the food they send out to their loyal customers. I'm very disappointed in this place as we have been ordering here for a while now. But fortunately for us there are many other great Chinese/Thai restaurants who  have better quality control and will not deliver rotten/chemically tasting food  to their customers.

column3: If you‚Äôre looking for a hibachi restaurant where the chefs do tricks with the food you probably shouldn‚Äôt go here because they didn‚Äôt really do that.  Instead, chefs squirt sake into the mouths of customers from a bottle and toss food at them to see who can catch it in their mouth.  I didn't find anything wrong with this and the customers seemed to enjoy it.  But, keep in mind that this is a Japanese restaurant, not a hibachi restaurant.  Other than that, the chef and most of the staff were friendly and the food was good.  The reason why I'm giving the restaurant three stars is because of some other things that happened while I was there. One of the chefs was Hispanic which pleasantly surprised me.  I noticed that one of the Asian staff members was constantly watching the Hispanic chef while he worked.  This man had such an obvious disdain for him that it made me uncomfortable.  He would glare at him and whisper to another staff member (I‚Äôm going to assume about him) who seemed less interested in what he had to say.  He never looked at the other chef who was working (who happened to be Asian) just at the Hispanic one.  Maybe he had some personal beef with the man, but it went on for quite some time and was so blatant that it was shocking.  There was also another Asian man there whose role and function was not clear, but seemed to be managing the staff.  A Hispanic boy was working there (he looked very young, like a teenager).  The man in charge started yelling at him and then he called him stupid before the boy disappeared into another part of the restaurant.  The whole exchange happened right in front of me.  I didn‚Äôt say anything because I didn‚Äôt want to make more trouble for the boy.  I don‚Äôt know what his situation is and he may really need that job.  But, to be verbally abusive and to do it in front of customers, I have no words.  For those who would accuse me of being nosey I say, I usually don‚Äôt notice anything going on around me while I‚Äôm eating.  Also, this all happened right next to my table, not feet from me.  Not going back, I don‚Äôt like seeing people mistreated in the workplace like that.

column3: I can‚Äôt comment on the food because I didn‚Äôt even get to dinner. My friend and I decided to try this place last night. It was her first time at Hibachi and my first time at this particular restaurant.From  the time we walked in the entire experience was poor. We were rushed about our seating choice and the general attitude of the staff was snide and not at all friendly. We asked for two minutes to look over the menu since I had gone to the restroom when we were first seated and the chef was inpatient and rude. It wasn‚Äôt even poor customer service, it was non existent. It was clear that this restaurant didn‚Äôt care to have our business, so I politely paid for the soup and salad that they placed when we sat down and left. On my way out, I told the waiter of our poor experience and he offered some remarks inaudibly and never looked us in the face once or apologized. We ended up having dinner at another restaurant that offered much better customer service and great food.I will not allow any establishment where I am spending my hard earned money to treat me poorly and I will not be returning to Nikko. This business can certainly use some customer service training.

column3: My experience at this establishment was not bad, and the staff was nice for the most part.  I was happy with the noodles, and somewhat happy with my filet.  While a bit flavorful, I felt it lacked seasoning.  There were a few fatty parts which is surprising for a filet, but it was definitely good enough to finish up.  The sauces that the chef gave us along with our dishes helped bring my filet to life.  My only concern was the portion size.  I feel they could have tossed some more noodles in my dish because I was still quite hungry after finishing my food.  Also, I asked for no veggies and was wondering if they could add more noodles or anything else (obviously not the Filet) to make up for it.  Nope, the waiter told me no veggies means no veggies, and that I do not get extras of other food if I choose this.  While I get it, noodles and rice are cheap to make; you think you could have given me something? These little things go a long way because the idea of eating is also not to be hungry anymore.  The substitution probably could have helped with that, but that is their rules and it is what it is.  The hibachi chef we had was quite nice as well, so I would overall say this was a decent experience.  I would go back if they upped the portion on the cheaper sides like rice and noodles.

really wanted to like this local Hibachi style restaurant.  They didn‚Äôt seem to be way overpriced (looking at you Benihana) and offered a wide variety of options.  Unfortunately, i can‚Äôt recommend this restaurant.   While the staff was pleasant and the ‚Äúchefs‚Äù tried to entertain you while they cooked you meal, they failed everywhere else:  1.  They try to seat as many people as possible around the hibachis.  To the point you are elbow to elbow.  Might be ok if it were entirely your own party, but not for a communion table.  2.  The food.  While the ingredients seemed to be fresh, what they add to it is way too much.  You can barely taste the difference between the different proteins.  I had steak and scallops.  Also too much sodium and oil.  3.  Timing.  They give you exactly one hour to complete your meal from the time you are seated.  45 minutes in they begin offering you boxes to take away and left over food.  At no time do they come around asking if you would like another drink, dessert, etc.

column3: Di roti hut is my go to spot when I want to get something to eat for lunch. I Work across the street at the Queens Village Post Office and I can‚Äôt lie, this roti shop has become a big part of my day to day while I‚Äôm on the grind at work. I‚Äôm from Brooklyn, NY, born and raised. But my family is from Jamaica so, when it comes to buying outside food I don‚Äôt really like eating fast food. And coming from Flatbush, Brooklyn, when I noticed there was a roti shop across the street from my new station I was definitely relieved. At first I use to go to the shop once in a while, but over the last few months I find myself going to the roti shop almost everyday. The staff there is amazing, BiBi especially was the first one there to really start noticing how often I come to the shop. Super friendly, laid back, and chill. I go there so much almost everyone there knows me by name. You can tell this shop is family owned and the vibes there is always nice. But above all, I‚Äôm in there everyday for the good eats and the great customer service that is provided to me every time I stop by. Hands down one of the best roti shops in Queens.

column3: Such good food and reasonably priced! I hate having to go to Liberty when I want good doubles because I don‚Äôt want to deal with the traffic and the parking. I love the location, I always can find parking that‚Äôs close by. I honestly have to say that the doubles are better than the ones you‚Äôll find in Liberty anyways. The bara is soft and it holds the curry channa well. The accompaniments definitely helped in balancing the flavors. I will say the pepper sauce is not enough on the doubles (and yes, I asked for extra pepper). I mean for 1.50 a piece for doubles, it is an amazing price. I also got mango curry which was fantastic as well. I also love that all of the meat is halal. It‚Äôs definitely a place I will go back to for a quick, cheap, tasty bite.  I would recommend calling in your order so by the time you get there you can just pay instead of waiting in a line. They also have a variety of Trini/Guyanese snacks you can buy. The drink selection is fabulous and the pastry/bread selection is quite nice as well. Definitely try them out!

column3: This is hands down the BEST Trinidadian restaurant in the area! Food is authentic and flavorful, prices are reasonable, portions are generous and the staff is very friendly and accommodating! Very chill vibe, always clean and well kept with lots of seating. Good variety of food, great vegetarian options and everything is always fresh.  I highly recommend the doubles and their corn soup. Their corn soup is some of the best I've ever had, not just in NYC! Bursting with flavors, all the vegetables and dumplings have the perfect mix of textures and just enough pepper to give it a nice kick! Doubles are the second best I've had in NYC (my #1 spot is a trek so I'll happily settle for these). Pumpkin, channa, curry mango are all fantastic and their roti is always soft and fresh.  The ladies are super sweet and also offer great recommendations and I've never felt rushed. If you see fresh mango chow at the register BUY IT, you won't regret it. They also carry lots of other trini snacks and soft drinks! Must visit if you're in the area!

Never had such a disrespectful experience anywhere in my life until i decide to step into this place. I was waiting on the line when a customer cut me off and i mentioned to my other half who was standing next to me. Long story short one of the staff a slim tall woman with glasses who was serving another customer at that time decided to talk to the customer that cut the line and make fun about the situation saying " why you cut the line miss don't you know you not suppose to do that" and started laughing with the customer like its okay with what she did. They both carried on for minutes while i was still standing in line waiting. The customer seems like an acquaintance to the staff but regardless everyone should be treated  fairly and wait there turn. My better half and I ended up leaving without buying anything as i was very upset and felt very uncomfortable. For me this is disrespectful and unprofessional and those types of staff needs proper training.  I will never go there again and i wudn't recommend my family and Friends either. Never the less it doesn't justify your staff behavior which was completely wrong , rude and unprofessional and you need to look into that. Do the right thing because of customers you have a functioning business.

column3: I‚Äôve been here a few times with my parents for dine-in dim sum pre-Covid era. This time, we called ahead for a pick up order on a Sunday for 12 pm. We ordered a beef/bitter melon rice, fried fish and tofu rice, chicken and salted fish fried rice, and a bunch of dim sum, which included the usual suspects. I appreciate the fact that they let you order dim sum ahead too. This way, you‚Äôre not fighting at the counter with the Chinese grandmas, trying to get your order in. Everything was correct and packaged neatly. But the actual food just isn‚Äôt as good anymore. The rice dishes were fine. The fried rice was packed to the brim, but it would have been nice if there was more salted fish in it, if there was any at all. It was also pretty bland. Dim sum is bland as well. The worst of the bunch was probably the honeycomb tripe. It was bland but just didn‚Äôt taste great.  Dim sum spots in this hood are slim pickins‚Äô. I‚Äôd come back for rice or noodle dishes but for dim sum, I would probably rather buy the frozen ones from the bakery down a few blocks and just cooking it myself.

column3: No frills. Just good food made to order.  We absolutely loved the preparation of the purple eggplant. It came out piping hot and remained that way for the entire meal. The walnut shrimp plate was a delight as well, I was super happy that even the broccoli was well seasoned. The salt level was great and freshness of the shrimp. The quality of the meat in the sweet-and-sour chicken was exactly what we were hoping for. Usually restaurants slack off in this department because it‚Äôs fried and covered in sauce but this plate did not disappoint.  In addition to these three main course options we had an order of white rice on the side and enjoyed the lovely tea. Usually we go to Chinatown for this style of cuisine but appears we have this gem among us here in Brooklyn. As we were eating we noticed a lot of people had some beautiful and extravagant dishes being dropped off to their table. Can‚Äôt wait to go back and try more ( like one of the meat platters or the lobster fried rice).  This place is definitely recommended for family style dining because all of the portions are so huge and definitely worth sharing. This place would also be great for a celebration, they have bigger tables and once all the food is on the table it all looks so beautiful and special. Not sure if they have drinks because we ended up drinking the tea that was served on arrival the whole time. Also we requested hot sauce and hot chili oil which is a must on the side.

column3: Delicious Chinese food!!!  Today we got lemon chicken (a childhood classic), jumbo fried shrimp, pea shoots, fried calamari (a staple for my family), fish with bean curd and mushroom, and yee-mein (remains as one of my favorite places for this). The lemon chicken was lightly crispy and had a delicious lemon sauce with a slight tang. The shrimp was slightly over cooked but still enjoyable. Fried calamari is a must order if you go here - the seasoning of salt, white pepper, and garlic are perfect! The calamari is perfectly tender and the crust is wonderfully crisp! Finally the yee-mein is something we always order here because it‚Äôs the best one (and I‚Äôve tried many!). Wing Hing is an excellent place to eat really good Cantonese food and we‚Äôve been coming back here for more than 10 years!

column3: If I didn‚Äôt get a chance to take food pics you know it was too good!  I did get a photo of my third round of drinks though. Both the tequila drinks, the comrade party and the cucumber margarita - HELLA GOOD!  So we sat at the bar and had Pat as our bartender/server and honey Pat was outstanding! I got amazing drinks, Pat helped me choose a delicious meal and even taught me how to say please and hello in Thai for my trip to Thailand!  The service was impeccable. The drinks were outstanding and the food was so good I forgot photos. We started with the chicken wings and rolls which were both soooooo good! The sauce with the wings were *chefs kiss*!!! I got the pad see eew (sp?) and my cousin got the bum Bo hue (sp?) and both were delicious. If I didn‚Äôt have to leave for my train ride back home I would‚Äôve gotten dessert but I didn‚Äôt have time so I just have to go back.  Do yourself a favor and go here, sit at the bar, ask for Pat, and make sure you have your stretchy pants on!

This restaurant is not even busy, there was no line outside and there were empty tables around us. Seriously, this was ridiculously humiliating, unkind, and unprofessional! Save your time and PLEASE DO NOT GO TO THIS RESTAURANT! There's more restaurant out there that are much much better!

column3: First, I want to give a HUGE shoutout to Jessica our waitress the evening of my visit. My friend group had not been together in several years so they were really excited and admittedly a little rambunctious. Jessica was calm and professional the entire time. Her service and coordination never lagged despite the distraction so kudos again to her.  The food itself was GREAT. We had a large group so we pretty much ordered everything on the menu. The Vietnamese chicken wings were a hit. I was partial to the Kalbi Short Ribs. My belly was happy as was the camera lens on my phone.  Speaking of which, I couldn't help but keep glancing around at the decor. It set up a great dimly lit atmosphere for dining. I'm not sure I've ever seen any of the elements used in any other space. We dined inside though I would've requested outdoor seating had I planned the shindig. The tables on the top floor were a little close for my comfort but not enough for me to sound an alarm.  Bottom line: You should go! Maybe you'll be lucky enough to have Jessica as your host/waitress. If you're driving, take a close look at the sparking situation. There's free street parking after 7pm but there's a LOT of traffic in the area so you might want to have a backup garage pre-booking.

column3: Appetisers were average but the mains were tasty

We went here (as a group of 6) for a late night 10pm dinner. The interiors are somewhat dark and the crockery posh. As I ate a lot of curry based (Thai green, Masamman etc.) dishes recently, I wanted to avoid the coconut milk dishes this time.  I tried the following. 1) Mushroom dumplings - They were soft and felt nice. The sweet tangy oily dark dressing was delicious. 2) Vegan Pad See Eew - Yummy, I saw them as south Indian kothu parotta (shredded multi-layer maida flatbreads) with Chinese seasoning spices! 3) Pineapple juice - Normal, but I poured almost half of it down.  The food was oily overall, especially the tofu in the Pad See Eew. The soy sauce-y flavour of the food was good!  One may see this place is slightly over-priced but for the elevated ambience and crockery.

column3: The food and service were wonderful. I enjoyed every bit that they had to offer.  Though spacing-wise, it was a bit packed like sardines. The ambiance and setting of the place itself made up for it.  I would say that the OBAO at Hell's Kitchen is a perfect place to go for a night outing with a party of 2-3; anything else and you will be overdoing it. ------------------------------------------------ What Lead Me To Come Here: I went to OBAO because I was planning a dinner for my graduation celebration. Making the reservation was not difficult, but the handling and confusion of the bill was. I made the reservation through website and called later to confirm my reservation with them.  Upon finalization, I received a party form that was sent by the OBAO staff regarding my bill for the night. This form confirmed the food that you've selected, the # of people in your party, and the amount that you will be paying for the night (which for me was changed as I paid at the actual place). In addition to that, they also ask for the payment method that you'll be using for the dinner.  Realistically, that was pointless to do since they charged me the full bill (including the additional purchases made) there. ------------------------------------------------ The Process of the Fee: - They charge for the party that you stated was going to come (So make sure everyone comes)  - Paid a $100 deposit fee ------------------------------------------------ My Setting: - Had a Party of 15

column3: Good Food! I'll give you the one star for that. 0 stars for BAD CUSTOMER SERVICE and RUDE host This was for Saturday, April 22, 2023 at around 430 PM I made reservations for 4 people for a 5 PM dinner. 2 of us arrived early and ordered drinks and appetizers at the bar with the third person following prior to our reservation. The 4th person who was visiting from London got driven to the wrong restaurant by Uber and texted me saying she will be delayed. They won't seat us as a policy. That's fine, and I understand that.  However, one of us had to leave early and would need to sit and eat. We already ordered our food from the bar and paid for it.  We requested to get seated and transferred but they won't let unless we downgrade to 3 people. The host vehemently warned that we cannot change the number of people if I did.  I explained the situation and said if we could be seated, we can figure out how to proceed when the friend arrived.  The host proceeded to seat us in a corner for 3. There was an empty table with 4 chairs. I said why not there, what's the difference of letting us sit at a 4 person table. They agreed. However, as soon as we sat down, they took away the 4th chair to make a point that we cannot have our friend join us.  I wanted to leave and move restaurants at that point but we had already ordered and paid for our food and drinks. The lost friend arrived 20 mins later as we were still eating dinner. Mind you, there was no line outside and there were empty tables around us. They refused her entry saying we only had 3 seats.  I waved at my friend from my seat, but the host was telling her she cannot come in because there was no seat for her.  Please speak to your friend, they only have a reservation for 3.   A restaurant in NYC that does this to their clients is not good.  It's unkind, unprofessional, and just not flexible when situations arise.  We had visitors from overseas, and this was how they were treated. There are tons of very good restaurants on 9th avenue and this should not be the case.  I was waving to my friend to join us since there was space at our table, but no chair.  The restaurant was stopping her from coming in. My other friend who had to leave early, gave up her seat to my other friend who arrived.  Only then, did they let her come in, because there are only 3 CHAIRS at our table.  The rude host refused  to give her a menu when she asked and only when my other friend left did they give her a menu begrudgingly. Their reasoning was it gives more work to the kitchen to have a secondary order. This is complete BS.  I asked to speak to a manager to explain the situation and complain about the rudeness.  She was nodding and saying she will speak to the host. However, she never apologized or tried to diffuse the situation.  I will never set foot again at OBAO, nor will I recommend this place to anyone I know. In fact, I will make sure to let people know how bad their service is.  Please, do not patronize restaurants that treat their customers like this.  Inflexible and not helpful.  We would have ordered for my friend ahead of time and they still won't let us.

column3: Honestly, this place isn't that good. I don't understand why their ratings are high. The food was very mediocre. The papaya salad didn't taste authentic. And pork belly was not fried correctly, and all you can taste is the fat. But the worst part was that when we were there during happy hour and they said it's half off for cocktails and sake. I ordered a cocktail without the alcohol and they charged me full price ($16) for basically berry juice. I'm kind of offended. I hardly leave negative reviews. But you charged me more during happy hour for a cocktail that didn't have alcohol! Never ever will I be back. The hostess was also kind of dismissive but the servers were pleasant. So I'm giving 2 stars to the server.

It is a famous Vietnamese restaurant (like Thai food) All the food was delicious and I would like to go there for lunch next time. However, the cocktails are a little pricey, and you can't enter unless you have made a reservation and everyone is there, so some people stuck in Manhattan traffic were late and waited at the entrance for several minutes. . If you are going, it is better to enter the store when everyone is present.

column3: We were a group of 39 young adults and tour leaders, in NY for 3 days (July 26-28). We arrived at the 7 Avenue location early in the morning and asked if we could reserve enough spots for all. The manager, without hesitation, quickly organized her restaurant and staff to push through all of our breakfast orders efficiently and in a timely manner - all done with a smile from everyone and kindness shown that was above and beyond what was expected!! We went there every morning for our 3 days and they again accommodated us without hesitation. On our final day we also had not only breakfast but asked for a carry-out lunch as well, which they were also happy to provide.  I would highly recommend this location and would like to give a special shout out to the manager. Her professionalism and organizational skills were phenomenal!  Thank you so much!!

We recently had the pleasure of working with Relish for one our firm events and the team delivered an outstanding experience for our attendees. The event flowed seamlessly, with the team efficiently managing the breakfast and lunch service. Each dish was served promptly, and the attention to detail was evident in every aspect. The Relish Catering team's meticulousness ensured that attendees could focus on enjoying the event without any disruptions. A big THANK YOU to Shoshana for all her help with pricing, menu selections and event execution!

The quality of the food and the level of service was outstanding. I would highly recommend Relish Catering and will certainly use them again. I was arranging this event from Sydney and found Claudine to be extremely responsive and nothing was an issue.  On the evening Tiffany ensured everything ran smoothly and the event was a success. Many thanks to a great team!

I've been working in the events industry for over 25 years and Relish is hands down the most professional, organized and incredibly delicious/tasty caterers around. Food is an important part (if not THE most important) of every event, Relish is my first phone call. They anticipate every next step allowing me to focus on other things to ensure the event is successful. They are a great partner to us. Can't sing their praises enough!

Robert and his team catered an event at Lavan541 for us and did a wonderful job! They were easy to communicate with, provided great service, and were punctual. I would recommend them without reservation.

Relish helped make my party a complete success.  I was able to relax and enjoy the party, as they took care of everything.  Food ws great and the kitchen was spotless when they left.  Thankyou RELISH!!

I used Relish for a book party recently and have nothing but positive things to say about working with this company! The food was fabulous, the pricing was reasonable, the service was incredible! Every member on the team was helpful, kind, upbeat, and extremely professional. Whenever I need a NYC caterer, this is who I will use from now on. Working with Relish truly took so much stress out of planning my event!

We had the honor of enjoying a wonderful lunch donated by Relish to our youth organization at Hunter College this summer July 22nd, 2022. Every summer for the past 17 years we have 60 underserved NYC girls attending the Bella Abzug Leadership Institute, inc. and we provide meals for them. This year Relish donated a wonderful lunch to us and the girls absolutely loved it. Everything was just perfect, from communication with the team, prompt delivery of everything, and of course the quality of the food was just superb. Our girls do not get to enjoy amazing food like this often and we are very thankful for such an opportunity and for Relish having picked us for their donation. THANK YOU so much Relish!

Relish was our VIP breakfast caterer at the 2022 Five Boro Bike Tour. The VIP breakfast was for 2000 of the 32,000 registered riders. Relish was professional and flexible even when we asked them to create another breakfast set up for our title sponsor, TD Bank, just 2 weeks out. As an event professional I appreciated Relish and their attention to detail. Not to mention the food was great!

I reached out to Relish in January to inquire about having them cater a corporate event for 100 guests at our NYC location in March.  Katey was a delight to work with, professional, detail oriented and intuitive.  Relish was so thorough with their preparations and communication leading up to the event that I had zero anxiety on the day of.  The food was truly spectacular, Katey managed the event on-site from beginning to end.  She was well prepared with a large team to support our event and we could not have been happier.  We have been met with nothing but rave reviews from all of our employees.

Love, love, love Relish! We are traditionally a family of strict from scratch cooks, but this year, my sister and I decided it was far more important to spend time with our families than in the kitchen. Relish delivered a delicious, homey meal that allowed us to thoroughly enjoy and be thankful for our wonderful Thanksgiving dinner. We have recommended several friends to try Relish and they all have been just as satisfied. Can't wait for our next holiday meal from Relish!!

Relish Catering has amazing and delicious menus, and a wonderful team of staff who make catering plans easy!! I have worked with the Relish team for several years and always trust the quality of food we will receive and know that it will be on time. Things always go according to plan and it makes my life so much easier!!

We have used Relish for multiple events over the last few years and they cannot be beat! From sit down gala's to cocktail receptions, Relish is without a doubt the best catering in the city. We constantly receive rave reviews from our guests on the quality of the food and the excellent service. The Chef is always willing to specifically cater the menu to our audience. Additionally, the entire team at Relish is a dream to work with. Highly recommend Relish for any of your catering needs.

We had a great experience with Relish, particularly Katey, our primary contact and Ethan who was onsite for our entire event. Ethan paid close attention to detail and was a fantastic throughout the event. Katey helped accommodate some last minute special requests and was very communicative throughout the process. We look forward to the next event!

I used Relish for the first time last week for an event, and the food was INCREDIBLE. Their team is friendly and professional and the value for their pricing for being in NYC is unbeatable. Will be using them much more for my company events moving forward!

LOVED working with Katey and the Relish Catering company! She was so responsive, and made working through our proposal so easy and straightforward. Excellent service and excellent food! Will definitely work with Relish again.
We hired Relish  for an event with 200 or so folks and it was fantastic. Food was excellent, service was spot on, we could not have been happier.  Would work with them again in a heartbeat!!

Unparalleled level of service. Attention to detail and an extremely strong core staff. The entire team has exceptional ability to problem solve onsite- coming up with creative solves to whatever issues pop up at live events.
Katey & Team were amazing :)

Amazing to work with! Claudine, Sole and team are just wonderful. Responsive, professional, and delicious food at a great price point always presented in a creative and thoughtful way. Can't wait to work with you again!

Such a great experience working with Claudine and the entire crew at Relish on baskets for a virtual event. From the beginning to the end, the entire experience felt personalized and like it really mattered to everyone at Relish. Top notch!

We are looking for to using Relish Catering at our next event.  Lux for Less couldnt be a more apporopriate saying for this company! :)

Every year, Relish Caterers helps make our annual benefit, Carnival Night for Kids, a huge success. It's a massive event with over 500 guests but they always stay calm, professional and organized. We know we can always rely on them to make sure the event runs smoothly and our guests leave happy and full! I can't imagine Carnival Night without Relish.

column3: Learned my lesson today that not all cubano are created equal! Visited on a Saturday afternoon and despite sitting at counter, enjoyed great service. The cubano is amazing with flavorful pulled pork, right amount of crunch bread, cheese, and ham. The fries are not that crispy but also not soggy - it is just right!  There are 3 complimentary condiments (ketchup, regular hot sauce, and habanero hot sauce) available.  The famous elotes is good but not as remarkable as the cubano that is worth coming back again and again for! Frozen margarita is also a must get that is complimentary to the meal especially on a warmer day.

column3: Get the Cuban sandwich. You will not be disappointed. It was so incredibly flavorful, and the fries were the best we had the entire trip. So good, we went back twice. I had the blackened chicken plate on one occasion, and that was fantastic. The sweet plantains were also delicious, arguably the best plantains I've had. This place gets bonus points for the atmosphere, probably the cheapest beer in the city ($3.75), and the sweetest family dynamics amongst the staff. The price of the entire meal was a great deal for Manhattan and one of the cheapest meals we had on the trip, while also being one of the tastiest. I thoroughly enjoyed dining here, and I think you will, too.

column3: Habana has lost its Mojo-hito.   Never again.   Was my fav neighborhood spot for years preCovid .   Sadly i'll never be back.  Food is not the same, smaller portions, exceptionally high prices - way too pricey for what you get.   Let's start with the Cuban sandwich - what used to be a massive sized sandwich and a generous portio of fire, so large thst 2 people could barely finish - has now been relegated to a tiny thing with 1/2 of the ham and pork, accompanied by a handful of soggy fries.  The Huevos con chorizo used to another huge platter of perfectly soft scrambled eggs with ground real Spanish choriz - now this is served literally on tiny side plate with a little dollop of beans.   To make matters worse, whatever they use now, (although the manager swore it was chorizo)  tastes like Jimmy Dean breakfast sausage.  Chorizo has a very distinct paprika flavor, and sorry whatever they use now is NOT Chorizo    either way the eggs were dried out and the "chorizo@ was cut into clumsily cut chunks.  I promptly sent that back and nibbled on the tiny remnant of the minature Cuban sandwich.  Not bad, just much smaller than it used to be.   To make matters worse. the service (which was never great) is now even worse given the large outdoor area which makes getting the attention of either of the servers next to impossible.   So sadly i won't waste my time waiting 20minutes for an undersized, over priced meal. - for the price and quality, there are now way better spots in Nolita to enjoy.   Scratch this one off the list ....

column3: If this was what I got from street food market or something like that, I would have loved it because rice dish I had was very flavorful. Fried chicken was crispy and juicy, all of meat/cabbage/rice/sauce in one bite had a very pleasant good taste experience. However, the restaurant was like half warehouse looking cause they stacked too many random boxes there. It felt like they don‚Äôt care or expect any potential dine-in customers. Table was all wrapped in scotch tapes so it felt so odd and cheap.  I'm curious about their other menus but not sure if I'd like to come all the way here again for this type of dine-in experience.  The taste of the food was quite good, but the interior of the restaurant was stacked with miscellaneous boxes, and the tables were wrapped with tape for some reason, so it wasn't a good atmosphere to enjoy the taste of food calmly. I'm curious about other menus, but the atmosphere didn't make me want to come back here and sit down and eat. I think it's worth a try if it's a very close distance from home, so it takes little effort, or if you can get it delivered here.
