Ordered through Uber Eats. Got the minced pork bowl (with cabbage) and a side of fried chicken. Food was delicious and quite fast when I ordered.  Food was enough for me and my partner to share, but we dont eat much. Bowl was very tasty, but also very oily (that's why I gave 4stars). What could be a relatively healthy dish became not so, although it tastes good The fried chicken was ordered mild, which is still a bit spicy, but in a good way. Crunchy, fresh tasting. Amazing.

I ordered the pork belly bento and the fried chicken from the snack menu. Delicious. Not a lot of food was given (i am also a 190 lbs man, both items were priced at a little under $20 yet...It was totally worth it. The ladies behind the counter were polite and the food was ready in 5 minutes. Looking forward for trying other things on the menu. Thank Taiwan Bear House for the most savory experience.

Made a visit to TBH on the recommendation of a Fung Bros video and was not disappointed.  The fried chicken bento box was quite tasty.  All dark meat pieces served on a bed of rice with a very good mince pork sauce as mentioned by other reviewers üëçüèº.  The egg was ok, as were the veggies.  All ingredients were quality though. Maybe a bit on the small side for 11.99 but no complaints.  Able to dine in at one of the two available tables after signing contact tracing form.
Yummy! Reminds me of Taiwan so much! Got the braised pork chop

I‚Äôve been craving Taiwanese Fried Chicken so badly since the Pandemic started. Thankfully the chicken at Taiwan Bear House is great! I also like that they load up your bento box with plenty of vegetables and an egg for balance. The pork sauce on the rice was nice too and unexpected - not my favourite version of pork sauce (since I prefer a slightly thickened sauce, and this one was more broth based) but still really good.
As a Taiwanese, imo the food here is really authentic. Very delicious! Salted crispy chicken is also very good üòç ‚Ä¶
Their food has no soul. It tastes & looks like what it‚Äôs called. But as a Taiwanese I know it‚Äôs still far different from the authentic taste.

One of the few places still open for takeout and delivery. Delicious bento boxes. We usually get the pork belly and crispy chicken. Both come over rice with some minced meat and cabbage on the side. Appreciate that they keep your order warm and wait to box up until you get there.
Authentic Taiwanese food, pork belly bento is my fave. They take credit card with minimum purchase.

Fast and affordable casual Taiwanese comfort food. Nothing too fancy. The Golden Crust Pork Chop bento box is a filling meal for its price. Snack order of the pop corn chicken comes in a large portion. This place is perfect for quick lunch.

A casual place for authentic Taiwanese rice bowls, including short grain rice with meat sauce, sauteed cabbage, braised egg and protein of choice (fried chiecken legs, braised or fried pork chop, etc). The meat is well-seasoned and flavorful. It is more expensive than the less-than $10 options in China town but you really get what you pay for.

It's Taiwanese bento. But the environment is a bit bad. I hope you can spend some time planning. The entrance door uses single-layer glass, and there is a 1-inch gap in the opening. It is very cold in winter, and you can smell the smoke outside when you eat. Inadequate storage space was not designed, resulting in the disposable tableware used by the restaurant being piled up in the common area. The tables and chairs are very uncomfortable, the tables are either too shallow or too small, and the tops are always sticky. Having said that, I still eat alone once in a while. It is a pity that it is not a good environment to bring foreign friends.
Good food

Can always count on Taiwan Bear House for a freshly made chicken bento box. There‚Äôs table & seating if one decides to stay and eat. I like their fried chicken thigh and popcorn chicken, not much of a pork eater but most come here for their Porkchop.

Nice fast casual Taiwanese place. I ordered a fried pork cutlet bento box which was $12. The pork was crispy and freshly fried, although saltier than I would have wanted. The bento box comes with half a tea egg and a small block of tofu. Under the pork cutlet there surprisingly was a marinated meat sauce that was really good. They also have drinks that start from $4, but I didn't order any. They accept Apple Pay and Google Pay. Didn't seem to have a bathroom in the restaurant and it is not wheelchair friendly. There is a step at the front door.

This place used to be really good 25 years ago, but now they cut back on some of the quality. The sweet & sour chicken is wrapped with breading filler to look like bigger chicken nuggets, while the chicken peices inside were actually small. (stringy almost ‚Å∞tasteless dry chicken too, not juicy)  The roast pork fried rice used to have huge 1/2" square chunks of pork, now the pork size is the same as most other chinese take out, 1/4" square.  I was put on hold as soon as he answered & felt like he was rushing me afterwards. All business personality, almost cold, like I did something wrong. No hospitality over phone, sounded like he was either mad at something (ratings?) or just having a bad day, everyone knows if your serving the public you have to appear to be nice as it might affect your business.  Then, the delivery guy (maybe it was the guy who took the order!) took $20.00 tip instead of $10.00 like I told him out loud for him to hear but he took my three $20.00 bills & gave me $10.00 back. My order was only $29.00. Real Slick.  Now that I saw that past review about the huge roach, I wont be ordering from them anymore anyway.  The fortune cookies were stale too, they didnt snap open just bent slowly.  The positives: They still give pleanty of sauces & a fruit in the bag & yes that famous Pistatio ice cream with cherries is still awesome.

I used to live around the corner from it, and I miss it dearly since moving to LA. It is equally great for an intimate small plate date, as for a few drinks and snacks at the bar with friends, or an affordable late night burger and fries while reading or journaling. It is a gem. Get the Burrata with squid ink if it‚Äôs on the menu - you‚Äôll be glad you tried it!

Came here the other day with a party of 6 and we had a great time! we ordered about half the menu and the standouts were definitely the rib eye and burrata. The burger was also mouth watering. They also have great cocktails. service was on point. Cannot wait to go back! yum

My wife and I went there for our anniversary dinner looking to have a very nice meal in a chill environment. The staff seated us at the table next to the restroom with a loud speaker while there were three huge communal tables open (those tables remained open the entire experience). We asked to move where they placed us in a high top next to the bar. We could barely fit so we eventually waited for seats at the bar. The menu seemed great..we went with the pork belly, mushrooms and gnocci. Pork belly was good but very big for two people since it's so fatty/oily. We were looking forward to the mushrooms (hoping for no something fresh), but they were underwhelming in flavor and again pretty oily. The gnocchi was a nice portion,  but they were in a bed of butter. Maybe we ordered the wrong items. The tastes all blended together and by the end we couldn't handle anymore fat without the flavor. For $150 on three items, we felt more taken advantage of rather than taken care of.

Went here last night and it was amazing! Basque and Colombian restaurant. The food changes from time to time so the server suggested that we take a picture of the menu and the drink menu to share with our party of 6 people since we were on the other end of the menu. We decided to order the following from the attached menu picture: (4) empanaditas (1) duck egg (2) Burrata (1) lasagna (1) pork belly (1) gnocchi with truffle (1) shishito peppers and (2) chocolate cakes (12) drinks and tip included, it came out to $407 for $68 per person. All REALLY good in my opinion but everyone loved the empanaditas. The duck egg was okay but our least favorite. Not bad for a Friday night dinner from 9PM - 11PM. Quick service and great environment.

column3: I usually prefer Neapolitan style pizza and if we go out for pizza it'll be usually just that. However, this place freed up a spot in my heart for a NY slice! We just happened to walk by here one evening in May on our honeymoon and decided to get a slice. The slice didn't just satisfy a light craving for a late snack but it made a lasting impression. Everything was on point. The sauce, the cheese - it resembles what I imagined a NY slice to be. Back at home in Berlin, Germany I sometimes just wish for a place that serves a pizza by the slice and then I reminisce about Encore Pizza with my wife. I got you guys saved in my favorite spots on Maps and when I'll be back to NYC I will 100% drop by! Keep it going until then! ;-)

column3: In the eyes of the average person, this is shwarma with a twist because it's kosher.  I love the  American and Jewish flavors added in the classic.  Of course they have other foods like burgers, kebabs, and regular chicken, but, the shwarma on laffa with various eggplant spreads, hummus, tahini, beets, and fries is by far my favorite. Indescribably good and addictive is all I can say about this place.  There's also a salad bar, but not like lettuce salad, but various pickled vegetables and some. I feel like I'm the only Asian person that goes there, and I get weird looks sometimes. Sometimes older Jewish men will ask me how I know the place and why I like the food or if I understand it. Always friendly people to talk to while waiting in line there.  The guys that makes the food are always super nice too. I just love them.  Surprisingly, the few times I felt I wasn't treated well was always right at the cashier when I'm paying.  I really have to say, the few impatient and non-caring cashiers I've encountered in the past 15 years I've been going is the only thing I don't like about the place.

column3: The food was bland and the service was slow; it's a surprisingly busy restaurant. There is no reason for it to be a sit-down, waited restaurant. At the UES location, this restaurant works well as counter-serve only. Frankly, everything about the UES location, including the taste of the food, is better than the Queens location. The hummus, falafel, and cabbage "salads" were all rather bland. The pita got really soggy before I could finish eating it. The laffa was too gummy. The french fries tasted like pesach fries. Note that the restaurant charges extra for using a credit card.  The nice things about the Queens location: It was impressive that the waitress/hostess speaks at least two languages fluently (English and Russian); it was a pretty multicultural clientele (Jews and gentiles from various cultures); they give a "salads" plate containing (tasteless) red cabbage salad and cole slaw as well as normal-tasting pickles.

column3: When I arrived at the Blackbarn Restaurant, I was met with a warm welcome and superb service. Despite being early for dinner due to another commitment, the accommodating staff graciously attended to my needs.  Nestled across the beautiful Madison Square Park, the restaurant's location is picture-perfect. The alfresco dining experience and the serene park view were refreshing and calming. The weather was in my favor, and I chose a curbside table shaded by vibrant red umbrellas.  My dinner commenced with a basket of freshly baked bread and a small plate of butter doused in a tasty sauce; both were served promptly even though the restaurant wasn't officially ready for dinner service. The service was commendable. The waiting staff was courteous and professional, showcasing the restaurant's dedication to its patrons.  The food was nothing short of excellent. Each dish was meticulously prepared and presented in an aesthetically pleasing manner. My appetizer, Bone Marrow, was made with Manila clams, a lemon-herb crumb, and a shallot reduction, creating a harmonious blend of flavors. The main course, Grilled Amish Chicken, was tender, succulent, and served with white bean and leek ravioli, charred ramps, garlic crumbs, and parmesan. Each bite was a testament to the chef's craftsmanship.  The pricing was very reasonable for the food quality and the service rendered. Furthermore, the restaurant features an onsite bar that serves an array of alcoholic beverages, making it an excellent place for an after-work rendezvous or a weekend night out.  However, there were a couple of areas that could use some attention. The staff, while courteous, seemed unsure when asked about the specific culinary style of the dishes served. While it was eventually categorized as American cuisine, it would benefit the team to understand the restaurant offerings better. The Diet Coke was also slightly off, being a bit watery and less effervescent than expected for such a high-end establishment.  The superior elements of the dining experience quickly overshadowed these minor issues. The decaffeinated coffee I ended my meal with was a highlight - rich, aromatic, not too strong, and served with an array of sweeteners in a charming mug. The ambiance and layout of the restaurant also deserve mention, as the spacious interior and well-spaced tables ensured a private and comfortable dining experience.  In conclusion, my experience at Blackbarn Restaurant was a delightful one. The slight opportunities for improvement do not detract from the overall high-quality dining experience. I eagerly anticipate my next visit to sample more of their exquisite dishes. This restaurant is a gem in the heart of Manhattan, offering excellent food and service at a reasonable price point, complete with an onsite bar.

column3: We are here as we speak. Very inflexible place. You cannot have a Mimosa with grapefruit juice, you cannot have any of their vegetable juices, you cannot have the salad from their prix-fix menu. However, if you want just a burger with fries, then they might be able to help you. We ended up ordering lamb ribs - touch as nails.
Top notch!

To start off, Blackbarn is incredible. If you‚Äôre considering going to this restaurant, don‚Äôt think twice, just book a reservation and go. To start, the restaurant has an abundance of room and feels like a brief escape from the city with all of the wood detail in the interior. Our server was very friendly and attentive, and was happy to make recommendations for us.  The first course: bread basket. This basket came with three different options to pair with a pat of butter sitting in garlic confit and flaky salt. Divine.  Second course: tuna tartare that tasted so light and fresh, octopus with a red pepper hummus and greens, and bone marrow with clams. The only dish I didn‚Äôt really care for was the bone marrow, but I think it‚Äôs just too fatty of a dish for me! My friend really enjoyed it. The octopus was well cooked and I loved the combination with the hummus.  Main course: fall off the bone ribs. Don‚Äôt sleep on this dish!! Even if you‚Äôre out at a business dinner, order the ribs. They used to have shoestring fries and have since been replaced by steak fries. We asked if we could upgrade to the parm fries instead and were told there would be a fee, and we were a bit disappointed to see us being charged for an entire side of fries, when we were under the impression it would just be an upgrade fee. It also comes with a cucumber salad which is a great light compliment to the overall dish, but our waiter forgot to bring it out and I had to separately ask for the cucumber salad. Don‚Äôt let that discourage you though, order the ribs‚Ä¶and to the restaurant‚Ä¶ please bring back the shoestring fries! We also ordered the truffle ricotta gnocchi and it tasted like little fluffy clouds of creamy truffle gnocchi. Cannot recommend this enough.  Dessert: bread pudding with house made vanilla bean ice cream, and a Granny Smith apple custard shortbread situation. If you‚Äôre going to order one thing outside of the ribs, make it the bread pudding. I would go the the restaurant just for that dessert alone. It was heavenly! column3: Simple: If you go to New York and don't visit Blackbarn you haven't been to New York.  It's not just the food, it's the entire experience.  The place is pleasant, it has a wine cellar with a wide variety of excellent wines, the liquor menu is generous and the food is a perfectly balanced combination of flavors. The products they use prove to be of the freshest quality and I recommend that you be sure to try, as an appetizer, the wild mushroom toasts... some divine tapas... but if you go in a large group then also order, as an appetizer, the butternut squash raviloli ‚Ä¶as a main dish, my favorite is fish (branzino) but the tomahawk looked delicious because I had the opportunity to see how they presented it to the table before serving it.  The desserts, then, ask them to explain to you that even the shortbread is produced by hand, not to mention the donuts.  Excellent service and the Chef very kind and friendly.
The experience was amazing! Great service, atmosphere and exquisite food! The Chef really has the heart in the food! Highly recommended!!!

column3: I celebrated my 40th birthday with a group of friends and reserved The Chef's Table. The worst decision of my life was making reservations here. First, for the price of such an exclusive table, the chef never introduced himself to myself - the main patron - nor the table. Secondly, none of the dishes were announced; the waiters rushed each plate while serving us: cold rack of lamb, dry BBQ ribs and flavorless pizza. Not to mention several other dishes that were subpar at best. The waiters would mumble to us then retreat back into the kitchen. My party planner was charged an enormous erroneous fee because apparently Blackbarn thinks black, professional patrons are "loud and unruly". She was falsely charged for absolutely nothing. We were a table comprised of CFOs, SVPs of major firms and city officials - why would we conduct ourselves as "loud and unruly"?! Thankfully, after speaking with one of the managers the following week, she was reimbursed. But not before him telling us that his waitress - a black female that was the only saving grace that night - was poorly tipped. Um, why is the most expensive reservation not kicking back it's fees to the main waitress' overall final tip? And why is their poor business model for their staff the problem of the guests - who left more than 20%?? I would advise NO ONE RESERVE THE CHEF TABLE. Not worth the money, aggravation, nor grief.

column3: Fabulous food and service for Sunday brunch! Our group shared four different offerings, all were scrumptious but our favorite was the rosemary waffles.

I will start by saying,  I am aware it was a holiday, but it was just not great. We had made reservations weeks and weeks ago for a special thanksgiving dinner . We arrived on time, just a short wait by 2 very nice young ladies at the reception  area. We were not happy with our table because it sat right in front of the kitchen swinging door, it was to close to the doors and it was busy in and out, this is the worst table in the place. We kindly asked if we can be moved, the waitress said to ask up at the reception area. When I went to the desk there was a different lady there this time, wearing a green dress, the manager. I kindly requested a new table and added that I had made this reservation weeks ago,  she immediately snapped at me " well so did lots of people" she was rude and impolite, plain and simple. There were quite a few empty tables available,  I said nothing else , just trying to avoid this unpleasant person on thanksgiving. We were seated at a new table that was just fine, the wait staff was amazing and friendly, the holiday food was just ok, the turkey was moist and good, the sides arrived cold, the desert was great. I understand the food being a bit off because of the holiday, but I don't excuse the rude manager. I took the high road.

column3: Ok, granted I only ate at the Tavern, but we did order some items off the main dining room menu. The food was good, but not great. The service was less than great. I Understand it‚Äôs hard to get good weed stuff these days, but there was hardly anyone in the tavern on a Sunday night, and our waiter seemed like he was may be smoking the devils lettuce. Super confused getting everything wrong and always vanishing.  I would say it was Hillstone level quality/food, I would have expected more creativity from the James Beard award winning chef John Doherty.

Exquite and refined a venerable feast for the senses. It was like being at every ski lodge but with an urban flair.  I think if they had a fireplace we would have never left.  From the sommelier to our waitress and the support staff we were treated like VIP which we are.  In addition we left another restaurant a favorite of ours in Kips Bay wanted to shove us in a two person table in the worst location after explaining that the refined booths were taken for an hour and a half later.  We were seated in a 4 person booth table at Black Barn with great views of everything including Chef John‚Äôs careful culinary experience and attention to every detail:  My beef shank was the best meal I have ever had the pleasure of within my world wide gourmand experiences in the worlds very best restaurants.  Also the bread pudding was delicious but also well represented.  It‚Äôs difficult to achieve style without pretension, Homey and cozy without tack decoration.  I‚Äôm sad to be so positive I mean I expect to be turned away because their so packed.  I am very ruthless when it comes to a bit of a 4 dollar rated place, but I tipped the staff 30 percent and would have delighted to dine at double the price.  Oscar Wilde said, ‚Äúone should eat well and live well‚Äù Black Barn is culture for beginners.  About the photo, Chef John on left yours truly Terry on the right

Bread basket was top tier as well as the rum butterscotch bread pudding a perfect way to end the night  Good but not needed: the tuna tartare was very good just a bit average to what u can find else where same with the shishito peppers. The butternut squash ravioli was good as well however it's very filling and wasn't a stand out of the night.  Could live without: the only thing I personally didn't like was the chicken wings. I got them for my sister who loved them however I wasn't that impressed. It was a bit too Smokey and tasted almost charred.  All in all this place was very good and I would love to dine back here. 9/10 overall

column3: Great service, yupdduck was deliciously spicy. Second time here and definitely coming back again.

Best topokki in the flushing area! If you can handle a little spice, go with the spicy version. It‚Äôs about as close to a bowl from Korea as you can get. It burns but burns so gooooood.  Also the bulgogi hot plate is a nice break from the spice in between each bite. And the fried dumpling work as the perfect crunchy vessel to dunk into the spicy topokki sauce.

I was looking for something to eat around the region; most restaurant nearby were surprisingly packed for a Wednesday. While i have heard of this place via social media review, i had never had a chance to try it until now.  Upon entering I found out they were closing soon, the waitress were kind enough to accept us as the last table for the night. I measured my temperature and recorded my name in accordance to the Covid-19 measure and sat down. I ordered their pork cream pasta and rose spicy rice cake with their mild spicy. The food came out relatively quickly.  I am not sure if I was just hungry but oh boy the food was good. The pork cream pasta's sauce is Japanese curry-based. While there was not a lot of noodle, it tasted delicious and well cooked. I enjoyed the sauce base so much i ordered a side of white rice just to make good of the left over curry sauce from the pasta.  the rice cake was packed with goodies. From glass noodle / fish cake / lettuce / sausage / rice cake...etc. The rice cake was well-cooked and chewy and the ingredient tasted fresh. I was satisfied and filled from eating the pasta and that we end up getting the rice cake to go.  even though they were closing for the day; the waitress did not rush us to finish and gave ample comfortable time to enjoy the entrees.  I definitely would return to this place again and try out more of the other variety on the menu.  Thank you.

If you want Korean comfort food or need some spicy food to perk you up, this is a good place to go! They have a variety of options and execute on them well, to the point where you would think that the cast iron skillet was born for fried rice, mozzarella, and corn!  I do wish they would make a few minor tweaks in the food, such as having an all white meat option for their chicken entr√©es or being able to serve their hamburgers with 100% beef instead of a pork blend.  The service isn't bad either and they have free delivery. Some of the servers seem shy though if you don't speak or look like you can't speak Korean. I try not to blame them - when I went to Korea, I kept praying the locals would keep the conversation short and not notice my lack of skills.  I'm also surprised by so many local guides in Flushing ranting about prices in this area, as the price range should be a separate category from the dining experience. Then again, guess we were all price sensitive when we were younger and haven't yet worked for a living - as someone who's done some analysis and commercial real estate before, it's safe to say that the price range here is right, considering the location, inflation rate (it's not the '90s anymore), wages (which translates to the cost of living in Flushing), and cost of goods. If you want to complain, then it may be more productive to write to your local reps about all the foreign investors and affiliated developers buying up all the land and parking their money here (note that many areas in and around Flushing is competitive with parts of Manhattan - and even more interesting is that retail rents has been generally falling there, while in contrast, is still rising in Flushing).

Its worth all the hype in my opinion. we also tried their soondae, which i thought was just OK, i doubt i would get that again. their bulgogi rice cake was really good, surprisingly good and a great bargain. dont get me wrong, their food isnt cheap, but they didnt skimp out on the bulgogi. i wish it had a tad more veggies. cause the rice cake can become overbearingly full. the soup that its in is peppery yet sweet. i wouldnt suggest drinking the soup. it was more of sauce, but liquid enough to be a soup.  Anyhow, you gotta try their kimchi fried rice. theres just something about rice and cheese that makes this dish really taste. there chips in it that gives it a crunch, corn which makes it sweet, bacon which makes it savory, and kimchi which makes is spicy.  All in all, i would recommend this place.

Came for lunch after hearing a lot about this place. The bottom line - food was ok but not at this price range. First of all, people have to understand that spicy rice cakes are street food (aka cheap and going). We got the lunch special with the spicy rice cakes and kimchee and bacon fried rice combo. It cost $28 after tax (note these lunch specials are sized for 2 people). At that price for lunch, I'm expecting pretty amazing. If this lunch cost $15, it would have been pretty amazing. Details: the food is spicy! We asked for mild and it was sweat inducing. My wife, who can stand heat, said it was pretty spicy. The rice cakes have a nice chewiness. The mini sausages (there were only 2) were really good with a nice snap. The cheese (I hear that like the sauce, it's imported from Korea) gave it a nice creaminess that helped offset the heat a little. The fried rice was terrific conceptually. But if you're going to say bacon, it better taste like it has bacon! This had no trace of the porcine pleasure. Similarly, not really too much noticeable kimchee either. Again, the cheese helps cut the spiciness and helps hold it all together. Service was good. But as others may have already noted, this isn't like a full service Korean restaurant so they didn't have any banchan. Also, typically these type of places give out mini yogurt drinks with the bill. Nope, none of that here either. We came around 12 and the place was half full. Surprising given it's buzz.

column3: I would say this is one of the worst Thai spots in New York City. On the bright side, the outdoor atmosphere was nice, and the service was amicable, but the food was simply horrible. Please do not waste your time or money eating here.  I had the pad kee mao and ginger sauce dishes with beef and while the portions were hefty and will fill you up, I felt that the taste and quality of food was lacking. The vegetables, as you can see in the pictures, look grimy and appear to not have been washed. I appreciate the abundance of vegetables on the dishes but there appeared to be some rotten cuts of vegetables that left little to be desired.  I found the noodles on my pad kee mao to be quite soggy and over cooked, whereas the ginger sauce dish was very salty and the rice needed to be mixed in to balance the salinity of the dish. I also wish there was some spice and finesse to the dishes served. While the plates may have been colorful, I was not fully satisfied with the flavors of each dish.  Would I come back here again? Absolutely not. I don‚Äôt think this restaurant does Thai food justice, and the quality of food and flavors do not reflect the vibrancy and essence of the cuisine whatsoever.

Food was not bad. For the entree I got  Pad Kee Mao drunken noodles with beef & chili sauce and it was savory, noodles were soft, & the chili sauce gave it a tiny kick with each bite. My husband got the Pad Se Ew. Their vegetables in this dish was bitter and tasted odd. I initially thought he was just being a picky eater, but then I tried one and had to spit it back out and was like whoa something is going on with those veggies. Also got their Mango Sticky Rice for dessert and again, it was okay. Mango wasn't as fresh or tasty. Their thai ice tea was pretty good and creamy, and loved it initially, but got too sweet towards the end. Overall food was okay, but not the best Thai food I've had. Their prices are a tad less than nearby Thai food restaurants so that's a plus.

Good crawfish mac, abysmal service at the pick-up window. Wanted to support a local small business by trying their food for the first time and picked up a to-go order. Unpopular opinion: expecting tips on to-go orders is out of hand; and I'm a waiter of ten years in NYC. Summer 2020 was a different story and circumstance. These days, I've reverted back a bit. If I've come once or twice to pick-up my food and we've built a rapport b/c your service is solid, kind, and memorable, then awesome - I'm happy to tip. Maybe I'm biased b/c my FOH team doesn't expect to be tipped on to-go orders, and I'm constantly comparing the service quality of others to ours.  Apparently, choosing to support this establishment is not enough. Your business is not appreciated unless you give the person at pick-up something extra, or they will call you out in front of other guests in line. There is next to no chance this business could ever get me to bring guests, run up a liquor tab, and tip the 20+% for decent, hospitable service. No interest in further supporting this business.

There are several Just Salad locations in NYC that are great, but the Park Slope location is a disaster. Terrible customer service, routinely deliver salads over an hour after the quoted delivery time, impossible to reach when there's a problem with the order, and on three different occasions have left the main ingredient out of a salad. As in- we ordered a crispy poblano chicken salad and when it came, 90 minutes later, there was no chicken in it. It amazes me that I keep ordering from here, but the food at other locations is delicious so I keep wanting to give them another try. Our most recent order of four salads was still missing after 90 minutes (quoted delivery time was 30-40 min) and when I called, I was placed on hold for 17 minutes. I was finally connected to the store, and they said they couldn't help, didn't apologize, didn't have any explanation for the delay, and we‚Äôre totally rude. For $16 a salad from a place down the block, you'd expect either accurate orders, or quick delivery, or good service...or something. Sadly, Just Salad does nothing right. Just Salad literally the salad bar of my dreams. They offer plentiful salad options, wraps, smoothies, soups, bowls and more. The ingredients were fresh and bursting with flavor. I ordered the crispy chicken poblano salad and the avo blast toast- a combo deal for less than $15. They have a ‚Äúyou pick 2‚Äù option where you can choose a medium salad and a smoothie, wrap, soup, chips & drink, etc. What a steal! The portions were large enough that I had leftovers. Both were beautifully prepared by a prep cook named Miles, and everything exceeded my expectations. If I lived near a Just Salad, I would probably eat here daily.  What I love most about Salad Bar, however, goes beyond my taste buds. Salad Bar is committed to sustainability and promotes zero waste and plant-based diets. Everything is served in compostable materials, and they even offer reusable salad bowls. Just Salad is also on Too Good To Go, an app committed to the reduction of food waste. Ordering through that app is a great option for those of us on a tight budget. If you are a salad queen like me, you need to try Just Salad as soon as possible!

column3: I ordered the largest boil plus 2 eggs(The Reels Catch). I paid in cash and it amounted to almost $80. I went food shopping next door at food bazaar. Got home and DID NOT SEE ME EGGS AND ONLY 2 CRAB LEGS‚Ä¶everything else was in the bag. BTW my bag and all take out bags are put into a brown paper bag with handles that are sealed (I could not see what was inside).  I called and spoke to the same person who I paid in the Restaurant. When I explained that I was missing items she told me with hesitation that I could bring the food along with my receipt but she doubted that the manager would compensate me because I could have eaten it already. I found this statement strange as the manager should speak for themselves and perhaps should have taken this call. I also want to mention that the receptionist was very pleasant both in person and over the phone.  The manager was there when I ordered my takeout in the restaurant and never greeted myself or anyone else in the restaurant (in fact she; the manager looked annoyed and disgusted). I brushed it off as maybe something behind the scenes was or had transpired.  This was my first time at Hook&Reel in general. I will not return because I feel as though there is some sort of intentional bias as I was immediately discouraged from returning to make a complaint to the manager and was told that I would be blamed and assumed of lying about the amount of food that I purchased.  I live in NYC and WE are surrounded by other areas that offer much better and higher quality seafood (some at much better prices comparatively).  I recommend not buying/patronizing this establishment. If there is already a negative bias/assumption of the guests you are serving then the service will always be skewed.

column3: The 236 East 161 st. Location I love Hook & Reel and frequent often at a few locations. I am glad there‚Äôs one close to me and for the most part my friends and family always enjoy. From the take out to the dining in. But This past Sunday Mother‚Äôs Day i was kind of disappointed. The food as always was delicious. But this time we was asked to limit our enjoyment to perhaps 90 minutes and I‚Äôm not sure if it was 90 minutes from when we walked in sat down or from when our food arrived. But no one should be rushed to enjoy their food especially when there were lots of tables still available.Also they didn‚Äôt offer Any usual specials and had No specials for Mother‚Äôs Day. So We paid more to be rushed out. This to me was a management issue because i have friends who went to  other Hook & Reels this same day and didn‚Äôt have this experience. It‚Äôs a shame to enjoy an establishment in my neighborhood and have it be distorted by greed and silliness just because it‚Äôs Mother‚Äôs Day and management didn‚Äôt know how to Organize. I guess they don‚Äôt mind risking the lost of valued customers

column3: I went here on Sunday with my daughter for the first time since they've opened up. I wasn't expecting a good outcome being that it's located in the Bronx, just being honest. I was surprised by the excellent customer service given from the moment we stepped into the door to the very moment we left. First of all, the waitress at the front greeted us with a genuine smile. (Not typical behavior from businesses in the Bronx,) She gave us a booth within a few minutes, wasn't a long wait. Not too long after, our assigned waiter came to our table and introduced himself. My daughter is very shy and quiet, so she's not good with talking to strangers. I'm sure he picked up on that and was very friendly, making her and myself feel comfortable. The whole time in between, he came to our table to check in on us. He was very patient, sweet, knowledgable on the menu and his vibes were definitely genuine. At the end, I gave him a tip but that wasn't good enough. I had to give this young man a good review online. The name on his tag is Kyle.  As for the food and drinks, it was good. The chicken was a bit salty, but it was also crispy so that made up for it. I didn't try their seafood so I can't rate that, (wasnt in the mood for it this day) Pricing was a bit high, but the positive environment the employees set for this place makes it worth it. In total, I will go to this place again, for sure. Good job to the owner of this restaurant for hiring a team of great people. THAT is what keeps customers like me coming back in the future, giving good tips AND bringing more customers for you by giving positive recommendations about your business. I'll definitely come back next time and try the seafood!
column10: ['Service Dine in', 'Meal type Dinner', 'Price per person $30‚Äì50', 'Food: 4', 'Service: 5', 'Atmosphere: 5', 'Recommended dishes Wings, Fries', "Kid-friendliness As I stated, my daughter is shy and only opens up to ppl she can read. Kyle made her feel comfortable and after leaving, she told me she liked the guy because he's nice and she wants to come back again one day. When adults are mean to kids, that's a red flag for me. Being that Kyle, and the other employee (I hadn't caught her name,but she has curly hair) is very bubbly and speak in a tone that's not rude, I feel confident about bringing my child or neice/nephew here."]

column3: I had the pleasure of dining with Kendal and I have to say, I was blown away by the outstanding customer service I received. Our server was simply amazing! From the moment we arrived, he was warm, friendly, and welcoming. He went above and beyond to make sure our dining experience was unforgettable.  Not only did he take the time to explain the menu and provide recommendations, but he also checked on us frequently to ensure that everything was to our liking. He was attentive, yet never intrusive. He anticipated our needs before we even had to ask. It's rare to find such exceptional service these days, and I truly appreciate the effort he put into making our meal a memorable one.  I can confidently say that Kendal has earned my loyalty because of his amazing service. If you're looking for a dining experience that is not only delicious but also accompanied by exceptional service, I highly recommend you go and see Kendal, you won't be disappointed!

column3: I recently tried their lunch box, and I must say I was pleasantly surprised by the value and quality of the food. I opted for the $12 fish lunch box, and it came packed with a generous portion of fish fillet, a spiced corned egg, braised pork, Chinese bacon, and a variety of vegetables.  The fish fillet was fried to perfection, and the taste was reminiscent of Taiwanese popcorn chicken, which I absolutely loved. While the size of the lunch box might be a bit overwhelming for those with smaller appetites, I personally found it to be a fantastic value and a satisfying meal.  I would definitely order their lunch box again and recommend it to anyone looking for a delicious, filling meal at a great price.

Keepin it real out here in Flushing Solid solid spot for some traditional Taiwanese food. Location is convenient and even better, inside a tiny food hall with bunch of other vendors. There's just the right amount of seats and still has the hole in the wall vibe. The dishes are authentic and traditional, if that's your thing then it's the spot for you. The popcorn chicken and pork chop are something that everyone will like. Will def return.

If it wasn't for Google, I would never know this place existed. I got a bunch of their bento boxes to share with my friends yesterday and I was amazed at how delicious it was. We got the salt and pepper chicken over rice, the pork chop over rice, the gua bao (delicious slab of pork, with some sort of crushed peanuts and brown sugar concoction, pickled vegetables, and it was Delicious. The meat was so juicy)! The salt and pepper friend chicken was also delicious and the broccoli and bean sprouts were cooked to perfection! They were crispy and yummmmm. It was also nice that they threw on some minced braised pork over the rice. I would definitely give this place a try if you guys want some delicious Taiwanese style food!

I‚Äôve been to another Taipei Hong in Elmhurst.  This one is located off Roosevelt in Flushing inside a 5-stall mini food court and may not be easy to locate. I guess the best marker is T-Mobile which is 2 door away.  There‚Äôre a few 2-seater tables shared among all stalls, but aside from the 3 against wall, they are subject to foot traffic and people who are waiting.  So this is really geared for carry-out orders.  I don‚Äôt normally order this dish because it always gets preempted by other bolder dishes when I‚Äôm in town. Today nostalgia called and I made it a point to get it. It‚Äôs listed as ‚ÄúMixed Tempuras‚Äù on the menu; I‚Äôd subtitle it as ‚ÄúTempura Bowl with Broth‚Äù.   My MIL is right that it‚Äôs a dish we can easily make with ingredients from an Asian supermarket, but the sauce that accompanies the dish is crucial and I don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs readily available in stores.  The bowl consists of chunks of Daikon radishes, fish balls, fish cakes, seafood tofus, and fried tofus soaked in a pool of the magic sauce, with a cup of pork broth served separately. It was very temperature hot and very satisfying.  The soft and crunchy texture is very easy on the mouth.  I got what I came for and I highly recommend this dish. column3: A simple question: does it hit the spot? Nope. I had the Bombay chutney sandwich which is iconic in Bombay, India. See the thing is, you don‚Äôt need to make it that fancy. It‚Äôs actually quite simple as long as you get the crunch, potato filling and chutney right. It‚Äôs also a double decker sandwich usually so the sourdough is a bad choice because you need bread that can hold the chutney and stick to the filling. Just use good white sandwich bread like they do in Bombay! It wasn‚Äôt a bad meal but if you have eaten the authentic Bombay sandwich this won‚Äôt hit the spot for you. The beets and lettuce are not necessary:)

While the small space that houses Bombay Sandwich Company may seem innocuous, the food and flavors at this restaurant are beyond comprehension. Admittedly, like many Indian Americans, I fall into the "nothing is as good as my Indian mother's food" archetype, and that usually leaves me disappointed with most Indian restaurants.  And then I met the Bombay Sandwich Company.  What started with a chance encounter with the legendary Bombay Burger turned into a fully fledged love affair with their entire menu. Each dish is beautifully crafted, well thought-out, and the flavors masterfully harmonize on your palette. This isn't just an Indian restaurant, it's a true innovation in Indian cuisine that's trying to combat Indian food's greatest appeal and drawback - the heaviness that comes shortly after you eat a rich curry or tikka masala. A good paneer or chicken tikka masala is hard enough to execute, let alone trying to make dishes VEGAN and without the heavy cream that has come to define Indian dishes. Now you can enjoy the richness of Indian cuisine, without the heaviness that usually follows.  So, what's the secret? After a few visits, I found out. It's the owner, her passion for the food, and the wonderful staff who come together to deliver perfection. Nisha is a genius. She's not running a restaurant, she's orchestrating a symphony that you can experience by ordering any of her dishes. I hope New Yorkers everywhere come to this place to experience arguably the best Indian food I've had in NYC or London.  Bombay Sandwich Company is so good that you'll tell your Indian mother about it. In fact, she'll try it, and she'll fall in love with it.  Bombay Sandwich Company - keep on crushing it. You're a 3 star Michelin restaurant in my book already and I can't wait to share you with my friends everywhere. You rock.  Raj

column3: Dropped for lunch on my way from the Port Authority to Penn. It's just a few blocks walk. Had the Chana Burger, Butternut Squash Soup, bottled water  and a custom drink called Ganga Jamuna that was very tasty. $22 plus tip. All the food was very fresh and very well prepared with excellent flavor.  The slow-cooked chana masala was far better than most up-scale Indian restaurants I've visited. Not too hot/spicy and not over-spiced, just the right amount of hand-blended spices. The bread ( I had two types) was very fresh. They wrap their sandwiches in liquid-barrier paper, cut once, to make eating less messy and so you can get it all in your mouth and not falling out on your plate/lap/table. Great idea! They offer a wide selection of both vegetarian and vegan food and a pleasant eat-in atmosphere, although a bit small on the inside right now, it seems they are expanding to an outdoor patio area walled off from the street. Keep up the good work!

The new menus at Bombay Sandwich Company have made this place my new go to! The Mango Chili Beyond Burger is perhaps the best burger I have ever had..spicy, tangy and with the perfect bun to protein ratio! And the Bombay Club Sandwich is a massive mouthful of the type of club sandwich reminiscent of the best gymkhanas in India.  The curries of their new dinner menu, aka Bombay Curry Company, are flavorful tofu or paneer in rich sauces that are satisfyingly thick without the use of heavy cream. The Paneer Lababdar is an elevated tikka masala curry and the Methi Saag Paneer is probably the best I've ever had... thick, bright and made without food color or cream. The perfect takeout dinner!  Great job guys!!!

I'm not vegan but I love this place. Think healthy Indian food without sacrificing any flavor. It's usually quiet which makes it a nice rest stop for a quick bite when you're in the area.  The chana masala is the most popular item, but French lentils is my personal favorite, and let me tell you about the honey fennel grilled cheese...  I love the concept of a grilled cheese (who doesn't?), but the traditional grilled cheese gets me down a little (literally) when it's loaded with cheese and butter. The honey fennel grilled cheese here is the perfect ratio of bread to cheese, and they use mozzarella which isn't as decadent and still gooey and delicious. The raisins and honey gift it a little sweetness, and best of all it comes with a container of hot sauce which is just the cherry on top. I use mine sparingly and save it for sandwiches and salads at home.

column3: I came in here one morning to grab something quick for breakfast. The sandwich line was really long so I took a glance at their hot bar. I saw pork dumplings and put 5 into a small plastic container. Five. FIVE. Upon heading to check out and pay they were deemed to be $10. These dumplings WERE NOT sized or weighing anywhere near being worth $2 each. The women at the register said they were heavy - yeah, heavy with thick skin and NOT with meat filling.  The dumplings themselves tasted okay‚Ä¶okaaaaaay‚Ä¶.but it was tough to get past how overpriced their hot bar apparently is. Person who paid after me had a small container with some cold fruit and was charged nearly $12 - unsurprisingly they were also shocked. Their breakfast sandwich and lunch sandwich menu seems decently priced for the area but their cold/hot bar is definitely not. I  should have known better so shame on me, but I‚Äôll do my best to never eat here again soon.

column3: Bagel Coffee Culture

I was surprised to see Google Maps prompting me to submit another review, but I AM more than happy to do so.  From Saturday, August 20, until Sunday, August 21, 2022, my life partner, another Gay male couple and I attended Flame Con 2022.  Flame Con is the premier LGBTQ comic con.  It was held at the Sheraton Times Square hotel.  Cafe 53 is very conveniently located on the same block as the main hotel entrance.  The coffee is wonderful, the staff is very professional and polite, there are indoor and outdoor tables, hot fold, cold food, hot beverages, cold beverages and lots of snacks, treats and a wide variety of options to satisfy virtually every palate and dietary requirement.  They even sell wine!  There is a key to the bathroom behind the counter and it was refreshing to see staff wearing face masks.  I was well taken care of, and look forward to returning the next time I AM in that area.

I have been to this deli for breakfast and lunch and it never disappoints with fresh food and very clean spot.
